<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Actions to Prevent School Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Saturday called for less violence in popular entertainment and
urged Congress to support his gun safety and juvenile crime
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
In his weekly radio address, Clinton tried to determine "the
root causes" of youth violence that have led to dozens of deaths
and injuries in school shootings in Arkansas, Kentucky,
Mississippi, Pennsylvania and Oregon over the past several months.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said popular culture, from television and movies to
music and the computer screen, "too often glories violence" and
makes youngsters numb to it.
</P>
<P>
"When mindless killing becomes a staple of family
entertainment, when over and over children see cinematic conflicts
resolved not with words, but with weapons, we shouldn't be
surprised when children, from impulse or design, follow suit,"
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
The president called for public action and responsibility to
the problem. Entertainment industry must act responsibly while
adults must better monitor what youngsters see and hear, and
counsel them against violent behavior, he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Clinton said, parents must guard against easy
access to guns for children and Congress should act on the
administration's juvenile crime bill, which, among other things,
would ban violent juveniles from buying guns for life.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also asked the Department of Education and the
Department of Justice to work with school officials on developing
on "early warning guide" that might help prevent school violence.
</P>
<P>
He also urged Congress to pass a proposal in his balanced
budget for 95 million U.S. dollars to prevent juvenile crime and
promote after-school programs for youngsters.
</P>
<P>
Clinton planned to console later Saturday families of the
victims and community members following the May 21 shooting
rampage at Thurston High School in Springfield in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
Two students were killed and more than 20 were wounded when
15-year-old Kip Kinkel opened fire in the school cafeteria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
