<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO to Conduct Mock Air Raids in Albania, Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- NATO announced Saturday that it
is conducting mock air raids next Monday in Albania and Macedonia
to demonstrate its capability to project power into the region
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
The Western military alliance first announced air exercises in
the two Balkan countries at its defense ministers council meeting
Thursday, but did not say when.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, NATO Secretary General Javier Solana
said that the air exercises, codenamed "Determined Falcon," would
be held on June 15 with the consent of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Fifth Allied Air Force Combined Air Operations Center in
Italy will be responsible for conducting the exercises, which are
designed by NATO to stop Yugoslavia from indiscriminate use of
force against civilian population in its province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that fighters, reconnaissance, airborne
early warning, tankers and helicopters will take part in the
exercises. The aircraft are provided by a number of NATO
countries. They will take off from NATO countries and fly to the
exercise areas for specific events before return to originating
bases.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that NATO continues to support a political solution
which brings an end to the violence in Kosovo, provides an
enhanced status of Kosovo, preserves the territorial integrity of
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and safeguards the human and
civil rights of all inhabitants of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"NATO also remains determined," added the alliance chief, "to
contribute to efforts promoting stability and security in
neighboring countries, with particular emphasis on Albania and
Macedonia."
</P>
<P>
Both Albania and Macedonia are NATO's Partnership for Peace
member nations.
</P>
<P>
NATO warned that other military options, including air strikes
against Yugoslav military facilities on the ground in Kosovo, may
have to be resorted to if Belgrade chose to slight the warning
from the international community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
