<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Cabinet Meets to Heal Rift with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber
Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah Saturday chaired a special Cabinet meeting in an
attempt to end a rift between the government and the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of State for Cabinet
Affairs Nasser Al-Roudhan said after the meeting that the
ministers discussed the current relations between the government
and the National Assembly (parliament) and ways to overcome
obstacles blocking achievement of positive and constructive
cooperation between the two authorities.
</P>
<P>
Roudhan said the emir was briefed on the outcome of contacts
and meetings held between parliament and Cabinet leaders,
which were aimed at finding appropriate means to develop
a relationship of cooperation and coordination.
</P>
<P>
The emir called for strengthening democracy in light of the
values, principles and ties governing Kuwait, which are dominated
by the spirit of fraternity, indulgence and responsibility,
Roudhan said.
</P>
<P>
The emir also expressed hope that everyone would realize the
magnitude of responsibilities and challenges that have to be dealt
with and all efforts required for the good of the country.
</P>
<P>
It was speculated that the emir might, at Saturday's meeting,
dissolve the parliament due to its lack of cooperation with the
government on a wide range of matters, especially on the
government reform blueprint. The main difference is focused on the
government plan to privatize the economy in order to curb budget
deficits.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Sabah has said that
his government can no longer work with the 50-member National
Assembly, which was blamed for hindering the government reforms.
</P>
<P>
The parliament's criticism of the "spread of crimes and
corruption in various bodies" in the Interior Ministry also
attributed to the growing crisis between the two highest power
organs.
</P>
<P>
The current crisis began earlier the month when a legislator
decided to grill Interior Minister Sheikh Mohammad Al-Khaled
Al-Sabah over his incapability of fighting drugs and crimes.
</P>
<P>
However, the emir's remarks Saturday indicated that he would
not dissolve the parliament elected two years ago. Under the
constitution, the emir can dissolve parliament when the prime
minister says he can no longer deal with the legislature.
</P>
<P>
In 1976 and 1986, two previous Kuwaiti parliaments were
dissolved for severely criticizing the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
