<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers on Saturday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The six-nation Contact Group for former Yugoslavia met on
Friday in London to envisage a reprisal against the bloody
suppression by Serbs against Albanians in Kosovo. They threatened
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic with a U.N. resolution opening
the way for a military intervention. This option was supported by
France but rejected by Russia.
</P>
<P>
-- Pope John Paul II called on all parties concerned in the
Middle East to respect the engagement they have made for the peace
 process, when he met Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat at the
Vatican on Friday. Arafat has called for a popular mobilization by
the Palestinian people against Jewish colonization and urged the
United States to intervene more actively to save the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The recession in Asia, particularly in Japan, is exerting a
strong impact on world stock markets. The new bending of the yen to
144.75 low in exchange rate with the U.S. dollar made the stock
index in Seoul drop by 8.1 percent on Friday, while in Europe, Paris
stock exchange index dropped by 2.56 percent Amsterdam by 2.56
percent, and Frankfurt by 1.45 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- The six-nation Contact Group on former Yugoslavia Friday urged
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to give promise before Monday
to stop violences in Kosovo. Milosevic will meet with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin on Monday in Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
