<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Government Disappointed Over French </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government expressed
Saturday disappointment with statements by French officials that
a divided Cyprus could not enter the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
In a short statement, government spokesman Christos Stylianides
said that "after the visit of (Cypriot) Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides to Paris and other meetings with French officials, we
were disappointed to see this statement because we believe it is
not helpful."
</P>
<P>
Stylianides noted that statements, such as those expressed
Friday by French officials, are "contrary to EU decisions on
Cyprus and of course to the position of the British presidency."
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac's spokeswoman Catherine Colonna
told reporters in Paris Friday that France wants the EU to
consider suspending membership negotiations with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
She said that "the (European) Union cannot import into its
midst the problems of the division of Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman said that "a country which is split in two
is hard to envisage," adding that "negotiations make no sense
if reunification is not on the cards."
</P>
<P>
The French statements were made just three days before the
opening of the EU summit, which will be held in the Welsh city of
Cardiff on June 15-16.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders agreed last December to open membership talks
with the Cypriot government, which started in March this year.
</P>
<P>
The EU's decision has angered the Turkish Cypriots, who vowed
not to attend the intercommunal talks unless the Turkish
Cypriot-controlled breakaway entity in northern Cyprus is
recognized and the Cypriot government suspends accession talks
with the EU.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus peace process came to a standstill last summer when
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash walked out of a
U.N.-sponsored intercommunal talks to protest the EU's intention
to open accession talks with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
aftermath of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island as
a bizonal, bicommunal federation through peace talks, but so far
no tangible results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
