<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debutants Croatia, Jamaica to Clash in Group H </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Croatia and Jamaica make their World Cup
debuts on Sunday when the two sides clash with each other in a Group H
game.
</P>
<P>
Jamaica, the first English-speaking Caribbean nation to qualify for
the finals, would surprise the world if they could reach the second
stage while Croatia, boasting many talents playing in European
leagues, is aiming at a berth in the last four.
</P>
<P>
Croatia's coach Miroslav Blazevic said his team would have a result
no worse than the European Championship in 1996, meaning entering the
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
There were also pre-competition spying between the two squads,
which have never met before.
</P>
<P>
The Croatia camp has reportedly sent unsuccessfully spies to their
rivals while Jamaican coach Rene Simoes did some reconnaisance himself
by attending a Croatian warm-up game on June 9.
</P>
<P>
There is reasons that he shoudl know his opponents better, who are
led by 30-year-old Real Madrid striker Davor Suker, playmaker Robert
Prosinecki and midfielder Zvonimir Boban from AC Milan.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian attacking force could be stronger had Alen Boksic not
dropped out through injury and coach Miroslav Blazevic has planned to
form a striking combinatoin of Mario Stanic, originally a midfielder,
with Suker.
</P>
<P>
However, the key of this formation reshuffling lies in right back
Slaven Bilic, who became the major injury worry for Blazevic after
suffering a groin strain in a friendly last month.
</P>
<P>
On the other side, Brazilian Simoes prepared his team for the
finals through a series of friendlies and forced goalless draws with
Brazil, Nigeria and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
In a World Cup group that also includes South American favorite
Argentina and Japan, the "Reggae Boyz" may just be able to dance
within the first stage.
</P>
<P>
However, Simoes warned that "If the Croatians aren't careful, on
Sunday they'll be learning to dance reggae."
</P>
<P>
Walter Boyd could be the main hope to net in Sunday's game as the
"Black Pearl" has claimed with 17 international goals.
</P>
<P>
Following a rift between Boyd and Simoes, some English-based
players could be fielded instead, including Derby County's Deon
Burton, who made his fame by netting four goals in four successive
games in the qualifying competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
