<HEADLINE> Australian, Egyptian FMs Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Starting his three-day visit in
Egypt, Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer held talks
here Saturday with his Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa on regional
and international issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Their talks held in the Foreign Ministry tackled regional and
international issues of mutual interest, mainly the latest
developments in the Mideast peace process and Southeast Asia, the
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Moussa and Downer will sign a memorandum of understanding at
the end of their talks on holding comprehensive consultations
between the two sides in political, economic and trade fields.
</P>
<P>
Downer will also meet with President Hosni Mubarak, Prime
Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri, and Deputy Prime Minister and Minister
of Agriculture and Land Reclamation Youssef Wali.
</P>
<P>
The Australian foreign minister arrived here earlier in the day
following a tour of the region which has taken him to Israel and
the Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
Downer will visit the Sinai peninsula to bestow medals on 26
members of the Australian troops among the United Nations
Multinational Force and Observers in Sinai.
</P>
<P>
He will offer Egypt an Australian-made device for detecting
mines to contribute to sweeping 18 million mines that were planted
in Egypt during World War II. 
</P>
</TEXT>
