<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mogadishu Residents Act to Curb Looting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The people of Mogadishu have
started reacting for the first time to the current wave of
widespread banditry and looting in the streets of the Somali
capital.
</P>
<P>
Groups of annoyed businessmen, intellectuals and religious
elites began creating local security servicemen to combat this
burglary.
</P>
<P>
As the former Islamic courts of North Mogadishu had been
crippled by the misunderstanding between faction leader Ali Mahdi
Mohamed and the chairman of the courts, Sheikh Ali Sheikh Mohamud
(Sheikh Ali Dhere), daylight looting and robbery on public places
including mosques as well as the civilian properties became
popular.
</P>
<P>
The latest was the peeling off of Mogadishu's second largest
soccer stadium which currently accommodated a soccer tournament
by Mogadishu's main 10 teams. It had been rehabilitated by U.N.
Operations in Somalia (UNOSOM) during their operations in the
country.
</P>
<P>
A new initiative led by Sheikh Ali Dhere himself has again
reorganized about a hundred former armed militiamen in the Karan
district of north Mogadishu. Two days ago, the new force has in
one of their largest operations rounded up quite a number of
bandits including the seizure of two sacks of marijuana and 16
bandits including two women who either sold the narcotic or used
them.
</P>
<P>
The bandits have been tried in a small Islamic court, where 10
of them were found guilty and each served 39 lashes in public
while three others were released after establishing their
innocence. Sheikh Ali Dhere himself and his forces have blazed
the two sacks of marijuana inside the Karan police station where
hundreds of people have watched in happiness.
</P>
<P>
In south Mugadishu, another new Islamic court has been
inaugurated in the Shirkoleh area by a group of businessmen and
religious scholars.
</P>
<P>
People in the capital have been talking about the renewed
peace efforts by the renewed Islamic courts and two of their
subsequent successful operations. Many of them sighed with
relief following their disappointment resulted from the failure
of Mogadishu's faction leaders to formulate a common
administration for the capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFRCS Holds Regional Meeting for Relief Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The International Federation of
Red Crescent Societies (IFRCS) is holding a regional workshop
here to train its members to handle refugees in situations of
limited facilities, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The workshop comes in the wake of the rise in the number of
refugees now streaming into Zambia from its conflict-torn
neighbors Angola, Rwanda and the Democratic Republic of Congo
(former Zaire).
</P>
<P>
The workshop which started Monday has drawn participants from
most southern African countries.
</P>
<P>
"Zambia has been receiving a lot of refugees from Rwanda,
Angola and Zaire and the skeleton facilities and skills available
were not able to adequately provide help to them," said the
spokesman of the organizers.
</P>
<P>
IFRCS is the mother body of Red Cross societies whose mission
is to fight against human sufferings.
</P>
<P>
Issues to be tackled at the workshop include the prevention of
cholera outbreak which is usually the chief problem in situation
of water scarcity, crowding and poor sanitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Urges Yugoslavia to End Violence in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
Saturday urged Yugoslav authorities to bring an end to military
operations against ethnic Albanians in the Serbian province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
It is perfectly clear to everyone that the Serbs are acting
with excessive brutality toward the Kosovans. The violence is
forcing the people to flee their country in an attempt to escape
the conflict, the constant threat of death, and the harsh
realities of an ethnic cleansing, said Chirac during a meeting
with Kosovo's Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova.
</P>
<P>
He said the international community should use all means
necessary, including military intervention, to re-establish peace
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"If they continue like this, there will be a great risk that
the conflict will spill over into the Balkans," he said.
</P>
<P>
France has expressed its support of military intervention by
NATO in Kosovo, which has been plunged into war between Yugoslav
security forces and Albanian separatists over the past several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians have fled their homes
because of the conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
