<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Refugee Crisis Eases in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The situation of refugees and
internally displaced people living in Africa is easing since 2.2
million refugees have returned home recently, said a report by
the U.N. refugees agency UNHCR available here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
As of January 1998, there were 5.7 million refugees and 1.5
million internally displaced in Africa, out of an estimated 22.3
million worldwide. Now the figure of refugees fell to 3.5 million
in Africa, said the report of the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
In January 1997, there were 22.7 million refugees and the
displaced around the world, of whom eight million were in Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, among the major refugee-producing countries in the
world, seven are from Africa. They are Angola, Burundi, Eritrea,
Liberia, Sierra Leone, Somalia and Sudan, said the UNHCR Africa
Fact Sheet issued ahead of Africa Refugee Day on June 20.
</P>
<P>
The year 1997 saw major repatriation movements especially in
Ethiopia, Mali, Mauritania, Rwanda, Somalia and Togo, according
to the report based on a survey conducted in April.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, before the seven-year civil war broke out in Liberia,
western Africa recorded only 20,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
However, conflicts in Liberia, Sierra Leone, Senegal,
Mauritania and Mali have multiplied the figure in western Africa
to a peak of nearly one million exiles, said the report.
</P>
<P>
With an end to hostilities in Mali, the UNHCR was able to
begin important repatriation operations in 1995, and last year
completed returns from neighboring Mauritania and Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
The year 1998 now is expecting repatriation beginning in 1997
to Liberia to pick up with tens of thousands of refugees having
signed up to go home from Cote d'Ivoire and Guinea, said the
UNHCR report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, despite continuing debate over a possible peace
accord and crop-ruining floods in the south, tens of thousands of
Somali refugees are registering for return, especially to the
northwest of the Horn of Africa country.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March 1998, more than 18,000 Somali refugees
have returned home.
</P>
<P>
Currently there are still about 400,000 Somalis, 346,000
Sudanese, 321,000 Eritreans, 268,000 Burundis, 100,000 Congolese
and 75,000 Rwandans living as refugees in east Africa and the
Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
By the end of May, more than 40,000 Congolese had returned
home across Lake Tanganyika while the UNHCR now is facilitating
the return of the Burundi refugees from Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Zambia, Congo (Brazzaville), the Democratic Republic of Congo
and Namibia currently still host 260,000 Angolans who fled during
the 20 years of civil war, the UNHCR noted.
</P>
<P>
However, around 10,000 refugees have returned so far this year
to Angola, bringing the number of returnees to 140,000 since the
UNHCR began the repatriation in 1996. The UNHCR now hopes more
Angolans will repatriate when the country's rainy season ends in
May.
</P>
<P>
Despite all the improvements, Africa is still facing a
critical challenge particularly in the Great Lakes region over
how to reconcile refugee protection with the security of hosting
states and their people, the UNHCR said.
</P>
<P>
Currently there are three lasting solutions to the plight of
refugees -- voluntary repatriation, integration in the country of
first asylum and re-settlement in a third country.
</P>
<P>
The Convention on Refugees ratified by the member states of
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) entered into force on
June 20, 1974. Since then, the date has been celebrated as
Africa Refugee Day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
