<HEADLINE> Bombs Found at Airport Hours Before Clinton Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Two bombs were found at the
airport in Eugene, Oregon, on Friday night hours before U.S.
President Clinton's Air Force One landed, an Associated Press
report said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Tipped by an anonymous caller, Eugene police found and
detonated the bombs in a culvert near the airport, where the
president was to arrive for his visit to nearby Springfield to
comfort victims of last month's school shooting.
</P>
<P>
The caller also told police there were bombs at Eugene's
Greyhound bus terminal, but after it was cleared and searched for
seven hours no bombs were found. In Springfield, a bomb threat
emptied City Hall but a search there also turned up nothing.
</P>
<P>
Eugene police was quoted as saying that the bombs were nothing
to do with the president.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was to make a commencement address at Portland State
University on Saturday and to visit Springfield's Thurston High
School, where 15-year-old Kip Kinkel is accused of open fire on
students in a cafeteria, killing two and injuring more than 20.
</P>
</TEXT>
