<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisia ranks second among African countries in
service export.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar in the capital on Thursday, Tunisian
Minister of Trade Mondher Znaidi said services account for 30
percent of the country's total exports, 10 percent more than the
figure set by the European Union for its member states.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics have showed that Tunisia's exports of
textiles and clothes stood 2.7 billion Tunisian dinars (2.5
billion U.S. dollars) last year, increasing by 8 percent compared
to the volume in 1996.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Latest statistics released by United Arab Emirates
(UAE) Ministry of Planning have showed that hotel revenues in the
country last year amounted to 3 billion dirhams (about 820 million
dollars), 9.5 percent more than those in 1996.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's trade deficit dropped by a dramatic 36
percent on an annualized basis from November 1997 to May 1998,
thanks to expanded exports and shrunk imports.
</P>
<P>
The deficit was 425 million U.S. dollars in May, the Jerusalem
Post newspaper reported Friday, quoting figures released by the
Central Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The exports totaled 1.78 billion dollars, up 14 percent in
annual terms from November 1997 to May 1998 and imports 2.23
billion dollars, a decrease of 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The declining trade deficit along with the increase of imports
of investment goods have seemed to reinforce Finance Minister
Ya'acov Neeman's claim that Israel is nearing the end of its
economic stagnation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
