<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tough Rules Facing Kenyan Bankers: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Minister Simeon
Nyachae has said bank directors and senior managers will in
future be expected to borrow money from the banks they manage at
commercial rates and other tougher rules.
</P>
<P>
The move, which include amendments to the Banking Act, is
aimed at further protecting depositor's funds and fostering a
sound banking system, he was quoted by Saturday's East African
Standard newspaper as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
The changes also require owners and managers of financial
institutions to ensure sound corporate governance in all their
institutions. However, no details were given as to how this was
to be achieved.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that the Central Bank of Kenya now has
the managerial capacity necessary to monitor the local banking
sector.
</P>
<P>
The asset quality of banks will be scrutinized so that the
problem of large non-performing assets, which results from poor
credit procedures, is effectively addressed.
</P>
<P>
He announced that no bank or company will be allowed to issue
commercial paper or corporate bond unless they are rated by an
independent rating agency.
</P>
<P>
However, immediate implementation of this measure will be
difficult given that there is still no independent rating agency
in the country.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the minister presented to parliament the 1998/99
budget aimed at reviving the country's battled economy, and this
also sent a signal of an era of belt-tightening.
</P>
<P>
"The 1998/99 budget... reflects two principles that can be
summarized in a few words -- fiscal restraint and a balanced
budget," he said in the draft budget.
</P>
<P>
The budget also announced plans to introduce longer term bonds
with an attractive lower interest rate in the market.
</P>
<P>
The first, a two-year maturity bond will be an amnesty bond of
those who with undeclared tax income may buy the bond from now
until December 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Although the minister did not indicate the interest rate the
bond will attract, it is likely that this will be similar to the
current floating rate bond whose interest is pegged to the 91-day
Treasury Bill rate.
</P>
<P>
This interest will be paid half-yearly and will be subject to
15 percent withholding tax.
</P>
<P>
The other bond will be a low denominated bond with a fixed
rate of interest aimed at small savers. This is expected to
increase competition for government debt and lower interest
rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
