<HEADLINE> New Gold Mine Commissioned in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Anglo American Zimbabwe Company
has commissioned a new gold mine in Nkayi of west Zimbabwe, The
Herald daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Production at the gold mine, the company's second largest one
in the country, whose present capacity is 30,000 ounces of gold
per month, is expected to rise to 40,000 ounces a month.
</P>
<P>
Anglo American was planning to become the pre-eminent producer
of gold in Zimbabwe, with a target of some 300,000 ounces to 10
tons per annum in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony Friday, Nicky Oppenheimer,
deputy chairman of Anglo American Corporation of South Africa,
said, "We need to recognize that the world is shrinking in size
as communication becomes easier, finance becomes more mobile and
trade barriers around the world begin to fall."
</P>
<P>
"To meet these challenges, we as a country and a corporation
need to make the most of our advantages and minii our
disadvantages as we compete in the global playing field," he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Oppenheimer, the new mine was a show of the
confidence they had in Zimbabwe's economy. He urged governments
in the southern African region to continue improving the
investment climates in their countries.
</P>
<P>
Anglo American Corporation operates a number of mines in
Zimbabwe while it has announced plans to open a 77-million-U.S.
Dollars platinum mine, which is the country's second largest.
</P>
