<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Rand Dives to Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's currency Rand
sank to a new record low against the U.S. Dollar Friday despite a
Reserve Bank move to shore up local markets by cutting the repo
rate to 17 percent from 17.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In late trade the Rand was at 5.3 to the Dollar, a loss of 44
cents in the year, after briefly touching a low of 5.34. At its
strongest level Friday, it was 5.225, local media reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel told officials from the Reserve
Bank and commercial banks that there was no crisis in domestic
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
"The point was raised and accepted that the changes here in
South Africa have not reached crisis point," Manuel told a news
conference in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
He said all role players were committed to ensuring price
stability, and the government did not want to see unnecessary
changes to the macro-economic environment.
</P>
<P>
Referring to banks' decisions to increase lending rates,
Manuel said the government was concerned about any move that
would dampen economic growth prospects.
</P>
<P>
First National Bank announced a rate hike of two percentage
points Friday following similar move by another leading
commercial bank, ABSA. Other banks are expected to follow suit
soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
