<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African, Zimbabwean Bank Make Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Absa, the biggest commercial
bank in South Africa, has bought 26 percent share holding in the
Commercial Bank of Zimbabwe (CBZ) for 50 million Rand (9.4
million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The deal, signed in Harare later this week, formed part of the
CBZ's privatization and signified Absa's entry into sub-Saharan
Africa, Absa group managing director Nallie Bosman was quoted by
the Saturday's Citizen daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
The CBZ is a commercial bank with 12 well-spread branches in
Zimbabwe and is the first bank to be privatized in that country.
</P>
<P>
Absa expressed the hope that it would not merely be an
investor but would also promote a closer relationship with the
CBZ by becoming its technical partner.
</P>
<P>
The CBZ chief executive Gideon Gono said Absa was a strong
international partner whose expertise in treasury and technology
areas can assist the bank in entering international markets.
</P>
<P>
Absa and the CBZ have had a health relationship through
correspondent banking and trade financing transactions for
sometime.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994 trade between South Africa and sub-Saharan African
countries has improved dramatically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
