<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Power Board Head Sacked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Uganda Electricity Board (UEB)
managing director Simon D'Ujanja was dismissed Friday evening for
causing big economic losses to the giant parastatal.
</P>
<P>
The UEB board of directors also decided to send six top
managers in the company on forced leave.
</P>
<P>
Frank Katusiime, a board member, was quoted by Saturday's New
Vision paper as saying that the managers were interdicted in
connection with the loss of three billion Uganda Shillings (2.6
million U.S. Dollars) in dubious financial transactions.
</P>
<P>
"We fired him and wrote a letter to Richard Kaijuka, Minister
of Natural Resources. We have been restructuring and clear
financial and procurement regulations must be observed. Any
procurement above five million Shillings must be referred to the
board," Katusiime.
</P>
<P>
Over 100 million Uganda Shillings (80,000 Dollars) was paid
out by the managing director in one day without referring to the
finance committee or the board as the regulations required, he
added.
</P>
<P>
D'Ujanga was appointed UEB managing director in mid-1997 to
replace A.R. Rutta who was sacked for allegedly failing to
implement changes in line with the country's divestiture programs
and minimize delays in construction of a new dam in Jinja, a
major city east of the capital Kampala in Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
