<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Hopes for U.N. Chief's Role in South Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Saturday expressed the
hope that U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan will play a positive
role in promoting peace and security in South Asia through a just
settlement of the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the U.N. secretary general will contribute toward the
resolution of the Kashmir dispute in accordance with Security
Council resolutions," a Foreign Office spokesman told a news
conference here Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who has written a letter to Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
and also had a telephone conversation with him, is to send an
envoy to Islamabad and New Delhi to promote peace and security in
South Asia, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the spokesman reiterated that bilateral talks
between Pakistan and India could be resumed unless they are held
on the basis of the agenda agreed by the two countries' foreign
secretaries at their meeting in Islamabad in June last year.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan has invited India for talks on the basis of the
agreed agenda adopted at the Islamabad round on June 23 last year
while India wants talks on the basis of proposals they sent in
January," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, he said, cannot agree to engage itself in such talks
with India because the Indian proposals are "unrealistic and
unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
However, he did not elaborate on these proposals, saying only
that they are dealing with just the "mechanism" of the talks.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman emphasized that the agreed agenda between the two
countries includes "matters pertaining to peace and security with
a specific reference to the Kashmir dispute." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
