<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Launch European Satellite for First Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XICHANG, June 13 (Xinhua) -- A telecommunications satellite
made by the National Aerospatial Company of France arrived at the
Xichang Satellite Launch Center in southwest China's Sichuan
Province today.
</P>
<P>
The satellite is to be launched in the near future by a
China-made Long March 3B carrier rocket. This will be the first
time for China to launch a telecommunications satellite made by a
European country.
</P>
<P>
The satellite, named Sino No.1, is the first commercial
telecommunications satellite managed by the Sino Satellite
Communications Company Ltd of China, which is engaged in the lease
of satellite transponders and relevant satellite
telecommunications business.
</P>
<P>
The company is a state-owned stock-issuing one organized by the
China Aerospace Corporation, the China Satellite Launch, Survey
and Control System Department, the China Financial Electronics
Company and the Shanghai United Investment Company Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the company is aimed at reforming the way
in which China's applied satellite industry is developed merely
with state appropriations and boosting the industry with the aid
of the market economy mechanism.
</P>
<P>
The satellite carries 24 C-band transponders which cover the
entire Asia-Pacific region and 14 KU-band transponders which cover
China and its neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
With an effective life of 15 years, the satellite will provide
services related to television, and sound and data
transmission. These services will include telecommunications for
the People's Bank of China and Shanghai City.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
