<HEADLINE> Neuharth: "Most Americans have better understanding of China than Politicians"  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- "My feeling is that there are no
more walls. If there are walls, they are walls of friendship,"
Allen Neuharth has said when he posed for a picture with a group of
veteran American newspapermen.
</P>
<P>
"The Great Wall was built to keep away foreigners, unfriendly
foreigners from China. And now, look! Everybody on the Wall is a
foreigner, because there are no longer walls between countries,"
said Neuharth, an American newspaper mogul and founder of USA
Today.
</P>
<P>
The 73-year-old Neuharth has made 10 trips to China since China
normalized relations with the United States in 1979, and he met
the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping during his first visit to
Beijing, in 1980.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interviews with Xinhua, Neuharth noted that the
on-going debate in Congress and the media targeting President
Bill Clinton's coming visit to China "is made by a small minority
of noise-makers, and I think the vast majority of the people in
the U.S. are very glad that President Clinton is coming here.
</P>
<P>
"In some ways, most of the people in the U.S. have a better
understanding of China than our politicians do," he said, "That's
because the American people are not so selfish.
</P>
<P>
"I think the American people are relieved, and admire China and
Beijing more in the last year than ever before because of the way
China has handled the Hong Kong handover," he noted. "China
said, 'We will have "one country, two systems".' They made the
promise and they kept the promise.
</P>
<P>
"I think many many people in America -- those who have an
understanding of foreign affairs -- believe that there must be
one world with several systems," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Neuharth: "Most Americans have better understanding of China than Politicians"  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"So I think it is very important from China's perspective that
you do not let the political noise-makers in our country put the
wrong thing on this, I can understand what might happen but, you
see, even President Clinton has never hesitated, never for a
minute, considered not coming, though the media made it look like it
might change his mind," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no anti-China sentiment on the part of the American
people," Neuharth said. "You have to understand when you have a
two-party political system, they love to argue with each
other. But the general public are not carried away with such little
things. And that's why President Clinton never hesitated about
coming here."
</P>
<P>
Recalling his dinner with American Ambassador James Sasser
Thursday, Neuharth said the ambassador told him that the Clinton
administration had never considered not attending the welcoming
ceremony at the plaza to the east of the Great Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
"If an American leader refused to attend a welcoming ceremony
at the plaza, it would be like the leader of China coming to the
United States and saying "I don't want to be received at the south
lawn of the White House," Said Neuharth.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about media reports on the transfer of missile
technology and political donations, Neuharth said, "I think most
of our people and our administration and our President believe
that China has acted as a responsible, emerging world leader.
</P>
<P>
"As far as the financial contributions are concerned, everybody
in America knows that many many countries tunnel campaign funds to
the Republicans and the Democrats," he said. "It's just that,
again, under the two-party system, the Republicans try to make
democrats to be ashamed. In our political system, illegal campaign
contributions are used by both political parties over and over
again. Most people just laugh about it, and say,'That's the way
our system works,'" he said. "Also, there has been no proof that
campaign financing was directly tied to any favors for China."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Neuharth: "Most Americans have better understanding of China than Politicians"  (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Talking about the Western media's current coverage of China, he
said, "In our country, the public thinks that our press is not
very fair, that too many journalists, too many reporters report
biased, or unfair things in newspapers or on television. That's
why our press is not very popular in other countries. Instead of
just reporting the truth, there are too many opinions that are
biased and prejudiced."
</P>
<P>
"Even American embassy people here think the Western press does
not do a good, fair job in covering China. They generally agree
that the Western press is too negative about China," he said.
</P>
<P>
Neuharth is also the founder of Freedom Forum, an international
foundation. Speaking about freedom, he said, "I think the free
press, free speech and free spirit is different throughout the
world.
</P>
<P>
"We do not believe that Americans should impose their system on
other countries," he said. "We think we should let other countries
decide whether their systems are better or our system is better, or
whether there should be a mixture of the two."
</P>
<P>
"I think the more you travel in this world, the more you
understand that it is one world, but there are many systems, not
just in the press, but in religion, in economy and in everything
-- in all factors of life, all sectors of life," he added.
</P>
<P>
"And if we understand that, we can get along with each other,
cooperate with each other in economic and business matters, be at
peace with each other, and still be different in the way we do
things," Neuharth said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
