<HEADLINE> Foreign Countries to Support Philippine Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from 14 countries
and the United Nations said here Saturday that their governments
will continue to support Philippines' modernization and
development under the administration of President-Elect Joseph
Estrada.
</P>
<P>
They made the assurance during their separate meetings with
Philippine President Fidel Ramos Wednesday Morning, according to a
press statement issued by the presidential office.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the statement said, the dignitaries urged
Ramos to be actively involved in international affairs even after
he steps down from office on June 30 by sharing his thoughts on
the many developments taking place in various parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
In his meeting with President Ramos, Xie Fei, vice chairman of
the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress of China,
said China will develop 21st century-oriented relations of good
neighborliness and mutual trust with the Philippines and other
members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
"Japan is still committed to support the Philippines. We are
confident that the Philippines' incoming president will continue
to pursue the directions set by your administration," former
Japanese Foreign Minister Taro Nakayama told Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi said his
government sees the retention of some cabinet members of President
Ramos in the incoming administration as a "good sign of continuity
of policies and programs."
</P>
<P>
A U.S. representative said ties between Washington and Manila
will continue to prosper under the Estrada administration,
especially in the area of economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the Arab world assured Ramos that their
respective countries will continue to support the peace process in
Mindanao by pouring in more investments in the area to improve the
lives of Filipino Muslims.
</P>
<P>
All the representatives are in Manila participating in the
celebrations of the centennial of the Philippines' independence.
</P>
</TEXT>
