<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq, UNSCOM Start Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and the U.N. Special Commission
on disarmament in Iraq, known as UNSCOM, started talks on Saturday in
order to work out a program for the future arms inspections in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The talks were held at the Iraqi foreign ministry building, with
Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz as head of the Iraqi team and UNSCOM
Chairman Richard Butler as head of UNSCOM team.
</P>
<P>
Butler arrived here on Thursday, leading a 20-member UNSCOM
delegation including Deputy Chairman Charles Duelfer and four
commissioners from Venezuela, Russia, Belgium and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The talks are under way, but diplomats here believe that the talks
will be very difficult. Butler said at Thursday's press conference
that he has brought a list of prior tasks that Iraq has to fulfill in
order to get sanctions lifted.
</P>
<P>
Butler called the list "road map," saying access to information of
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, biological weapons in particular,
is the main prior task.
</P>
<P>
However, Iraq has declared time and again that it has destroyed all
its banned weapons and provided all necessary materials, documents and
information.
</P>
<P>
On a working visit to New York earlier this month, Iraqi Foreign
Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf slammed the "road map" as "political
motivated" with the aim to "complicate the situation."
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq has implemented all requirements under the U.N.
resolutions, urging that sanctions be lifted immediately.
</P>
<P>
Butler will continue his talks with Aziz on Sunday, and will leave
here next Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
