<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ICCPR Firmly Rooted in HK Legal System: Justice Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The International Covenant on
Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR) is firmly rooted in the legal
system of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR),
Secretary of Justice Elsie Leung said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Members of the community in Hong Kong are able to challenge
laws and procedures that they consider to be inconsistent with the
ICCPR, and in some cases those challenges have been successful,
Leung told the International Bar Association Conference on the
Worldwide Application of the ICCPR.
</P>
<P>
Leung said since the reunification the ICCPR has been given a
special status in Hong Kong by virtue of Article 39 of the Basic
Law.
</P>
<P>
"The Basic Law provides that provisions of the ICCPR as applied
to Hong Kong shall remain in force and shall be implemented
through the laws of the SAR.
</P>
<P>
"It also provides that the rights and freedoms enjoyed by Hong
Kong residents shall not be restricted unless as prescribed by
law, and that such restrictions shall not contravene the above
provisions," she said.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing some of the significant legal developments in the
past 12 months, Leung said some of these developments have been
the subject of criticism, but when properly understood in the
context of the resumption of Chinese sovereignty over Hong Kong,
they were fully justified and were consistent with the SAR's
obligations under ICCPR.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the amendments to the Societies Ordinance and
Public Order ordinance enacted on July 1, 1997, Leung told
participants of the conference that care was taken to ensure that
restrictions imposed on freedom of association and freedom of
assembly were consistent with the ICCPR.
</P>
<P>
"The amendments were subject to some criticism at the time they
were made. Some feared that they indicated an approach that was
hostile to human rights. That fear was misplaced," Leung said.
</P>
<P>
"The amendments struck the right balance between civil
liberties and social order. They reflected both the ICCPR and the
basic Law and, as I am sure you can see for yourselves, political
activities and demonstrations in Hong Kong remain as lively as
ever," Leung said.
</P>
<P>
To illustrate her point, Leung pointed out that from July 1,
1997 to March 31, 1998, there were over 1,260 public
demonstrations in Hong Kong and 626 societies formed.
</P>
<P>
Turning to court challenges that have been made to some of the
Ordinances enacted by the Provisional Legislative Council (PLC)
such as the immigration legislation which introduced the
Certificate of Entitlement Scheme, Leung said those challenges
have been made possible after Hong Kong's return to China because,
for the first time, Hong Kong now has a detailed written
constitution.
</P>
<P>
These court challenges demonstrated that human rights were
fully protected in the SAR by an independent judiciary, and that
the rule of law was as strong as ever, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transport Network Ready For Opening of New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 13 (Xinhua) -- An extensive public transport
network will go into operation progressively starting from late
this month to get ready for the opening of the new Hong Kong
International Airport at Chek Lap Kok on July 6, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Dorothy Chan, Deputy Commissioner for Transport, told a press
conference here Saturday: "Different models of public transport
services at different price ranges will be available for airport
bound passengers."
</P>
<P>
Commuters can choose among diversified means of transport,
including railway, bus, taxi and ferry, to get to the new airport,
which is situated on the north of Lantau, an outlying island in
the west of the Hong Kong Island.
</P>
<P>
The public transport network serving the new airport will be
introduced in two main phases, said Chan.
</P>
<P>
The first stage will start on June 22 with the commissioning of
the Tung Chung Line, a 30.5-km railway running from the downtown
district in Hong Kong to the Tung Chung Town in the north of
Lantau. On the same day, bus and taxi services on some routes will
start.
</P>
<P>
On June 30, regular high-speed ferries will begin to sail
between Chek Lap Kok and Tuen Men, in the southwest of the New
Territories.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the second phase will be in tandem with the full
opening of the new airport on July 6, when a purposely-built
railway linking Hong Kong, Kowloon and Chek Lap Kok is scheduled
for operation. The 34-km Airport Express Line can take passengers
to the airport in just 23 minutes, with trains rushing at a speed
of 135 km per hour.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 franchise buses will be deployed on the routes on the
opening day of the new airport and taxis will be in full service,
according to the official.  
</P>
