<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Negative GNP Growth Reported in Macao in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The growth rate of Macao's gross
national product (GNP) showed a negative growth for a second year
running in 1997, the Macao Daily News said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted official statistics as saying that the GNP growth
was estimated at -0.1 percent last year, comparing a -0.3 percent
growth rate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Macao has suffered from an economic slowdown since 1993. During
the past two years, nearly all its leading economic sectors --
tourism, foreign trade, real estate and finance -- reported
recession.
</P>
<P>
Tourist arrivals to Macao reached 7 million in 1997, down more
than 10 percent from 1996. Although foreign trade recorded growth,
real estate business and finance scored little progress.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, foreign trade in the first quarter of this year
resulted in a 1.8 billion patacas (about 225 million U.S. dollars)
of deficit, compared to a trade surplus last year. Retail sales in
the first three months also dropped 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said that Macao's mini-economy is subject to
external factors more than internal ones. The recession in the
past two years was attributed to financial storms in Asia as well
as security problems in Macao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
