<HEADLINE> Pak PM Reiterates Desire for Talks with India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
reiterated Saturday Pakistan's desire for meaningful talks with
India to settle all disputed issues between the two countries,
including Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Talking to the reporters here before his departure to
Manchester, the United Kingdom, the prime minister said Pakistan
is always prepared for talks with India to reduce tension in the
south Asian region.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan does not want to remain in a situation of hang up,"
said Sharif. He hoped that India would respond positively to
Pakistan's offer for talks and come forward to resolve the core
issue of Kashmir, which, he said, is a flash point for peace in
the region.
</P>
<P>
"We want to solve the Kashmir issue because we believe that it
would result dangerous arms race," said Sharif, adding that the
nuclear tests have brought the Kashmir issue out of the cold
storage.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister said that "first, the world should force
India to stop human rights violations in the held Kashmir, and
second hold plebiscite according to the United Nations
resolutions."
</P>
<P>
During his four-day stay in the United Kingdom, Sharif,
accompanied by Information Minister Mushahid Hussain and Minister
of State for Water and Power Haleem Siddique, will meet overseas
Pakistanis and address meetings at London and Manchester. 
</P>
