<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rafsanjani Blamed Over Tehran Mayor's Corrupt Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 13 (Xinhua) -- As factional struggles intensified in
the country, Iranian Former President Hashemi Rafsanjani was once
again targeted by the conservatives over the corrupt case of the
suspended Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi.
</P>
<P>
"From the legal point of view, the superiors of the Tehran mayor
are also guilty of breaking the law," local daily Iran News on
Saturday quoted Majlis (parliament) deputy Ali Zadsar Jirofti as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that Karbaschi's superiors, particularly Rafsanjani, should
have stood up to Karbaschi and stopped the mayor's violations of the
law. But regretfully Rafsanjani encouraged Karbaschi in stead of
stopping him, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Jirofti did not specify how Rafsanjani encouraged
Karbaschi, who is under an open trial on corrupt charges.
</P>
<P>
In April, another conservative Majlis deputy Ahmad Rasoulinejad
strongly lashed out at Rafsanjani for defending Karbaschi, warning
that he would release documents to show the involvement of
Rafsanjani's relatives in Karbaschi's case.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani, chairman of the powerful arbitrating body the State
Expediency Council, openly defended Karbaschi, blaming the factional
political row over the case as a "bitter" experience for the country
and the Islamic regime.
</P>
<P>
Karbaschi was detained on April 4 by the conservative judiciary on
embezzlement charges but was released after an 11-day imprisonment
upon an order from the supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei following
an appeal by President Mohammad Khatami and intervention by
Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
The mayor's case provoked a white-hot political struggle between
the conservatives and the moderates. The moderates accused their
rivals of undermining the government of Khatami while the
conservatives lashed out at the moderates for abusing freedom and
democracy.
</P>
<P>
The judiciary started an open trial on the suspended mayor on
June 7. Karbaschi rejected all accusations as "baseless," saying
that "I never stole a single rial."
</P>
<P>
However, Jirofti stressed that Karbaschi should be considered a
lawbreaker who tried to bypass the basic institutions of democracy,
saying Karbaschi "ignored the law and considered his own opinions
and judgments to be the law."
</P>
<P>
Iranian legal experts said that Karbaschi could face five years
in prison, a ban on holding government office, the return of funds
allegedly embezzled and a fine equivalent to twice the sum embezzled
if he was found guilty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
