<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leopard Killed in W. Kenya to Save Man </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Five young ethnic Maasai warriors
living in western Kenya killed a marauding leopard after a
five-hour fight Friday to save a 50-year-old man who was attacked
by the wild animal, local press reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Silili ole Olofikany of Nairasirara village in Narok said he
was going to his shamba (a small farm ) when he saw a leopard
kill two of his goats.
</P>
<P>
Trying to save the rest of his herd, Olofikany fought the
animal only with a rungu (knobkerrie) and a sword for more than
one hour, and suffered from serious injuries all over his body.
</P>
<P>
The five young men came to his rescue after hearing his
screams.
</P>
<P>
Using spears and metal-studded rungus, the young men killed
the leopard, skinned it and took the mutilated skin to the Kenya
Wildlife Service (KWS) warden at Ewaso Nyiro.
</P>
<P>
A brother of the injured man, Sarun ole Olofikany, said they
would kill all the wildlife in the area since KWS has failed to
drive them off.
</P>
<P>
They complained they had lost more than 100 goats to leopards
that have been roaming the area, forcing parents to escort their
children to and from school.
</P>
<P>
The villagers claimed they have not had a good harvest for a
number of years following destruction of food crops by elephants,
buffalos, zebras and antelopes.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, he said, their livestock continued being
killed by lions, leopards and cheetahs.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 percent of the wild animals in Kenya live out of
sanctuaries and game parks, leading to quite frequent conflicts
between human beings and animals who have to fight for their own
survival. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Lowers Cash Ratio Rule for Local Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya (CBK)
has announced a lower cash ratio requirement for commercial banks
to be effective from July 1.
</P>
<P>
Reuben Marambii, the chief banking manager, reduced the cash
ratio requirement from 15 percent to 14 percent Friday, the Daily
Nation newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The cash ratio is the percentage of total deposits that banks
and financial institutions must deposit with the central bank.
The cash attracts no interest, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Banks are required to observe the cash ratio rule and
forwarding the money to CBK. This is one of the tools used by
CBK to check money supply and inflation.
</P>
<P>
In a circular to commercial banks and financial institutions,
Marambii also reduced the daily cash ratio rule from 12 percent
to 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
A lower cash ratio requirement was announced by Finance
Minister Simeon Nyachae when presenting the budget for 1998/99
(July 1/June 30) to parliament on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The reduction in cash ratio should assist commercial banks in
their effort to bring down interest rates," said Marambii.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates on 91-day Treasury bills stand at over 25
percent, with commercial banks' base rates averaging around 28
percent.
</P>
<P>
In the money market, the Shilling hardly moved despite strong
inflows from coffee and tea exports as dealers waited for details
of the budget proposals.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said while Nyachae put focus on achieving a balanced
budget in the 1998/99 fiscal year, his comments on reducing
domestic debt and improving infrastructure and efficiency of the
public sector will be welcomed by the business community.
</P>
<P>
The minister said CBK is to introduce a two-year maturity
Treasury Bond with interest payable semi-annually, which will
carry a tax waiver and amnesty for investors.
</P>
<P>
The foreign exchange market was expected to remain calm as
analysts and corporations digest the long-term implications of
the budget.
</P>
<P>
CBK posted a Shilling mean rate of 61.19 against one U.S.
Dollar Friday, slightly weaker compared to 61.11 Thursday. It
posted a buying rate of 61 Shillings to the Dollar and a selling
rate of 61.33 Shillings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
