<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Vice President Specioza
Kazibwe said the government takes the blame for the June 8
massacre in which some 80 students were burnt to death by rebels
of Allied Democratic Forces (ADF).
</P>
<P>
Kazibwe made the statement when addressing a rally Friday at
the Kichwamba National Technical College in Kabarole district,
west Uganda.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, the government takes the blame for this massacre. There
was a problem with the institution that is constitutionally
supposed to protect all Ugandans. But this problem will be
rectified and the people should not lose hope," the vice
president was quoted by Saturday's New Vision daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Our children have been massacred, but not in vain. Their
blood should give us the strength to continue and accomplish the
struggle for the total liberation of the country from the
ruthless ADF and LRA (Lord Resistance Army)," she added.
</P>
<P>
As a counter measure against the rebels now active in the west
and north Uganda, she said, the government will train and arm
more home guards to protect people in the war-disturbed areas.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has increased its defense budget by 26 percent in the
coming fiscal year to boost the capacity of the army and end the
insurgency.
</P>
<P>
She called upon all Ugandans to join hands in fighting their
common enemy. She also promised to mobilize resources and assist
the bereaved families through the social welfare ministry.
</P>
