<HEADLINE> World Cup hke -- Old vs New: Theme of Argentina-Japan Clash    by Cao Li </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOULOUSE, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Argentina will on Sunday face the
challenge from Japan in the Group H opener between the traditional
South American powerhouse and the Asian debutants at the World Cup
finals.
</P>
<P>
Three-time winners Argentina are this time without the magic
elements from striker Diego Maradona, who brought disgrace rather than
glory to his motherland with a humiliating doping ban halfway down the
last World Cup in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the missing of their star striker Gabriel Batistuta
from Friday's training session reflected coach Daniel Passarella's
discretion in preserving their striking power.
</P>
<P>
The Fiorentina player hurt his left ankle in a practice game on
Thursday but Passarella explained his omission "was just a
precaution."
</P>
<P>
"Batistuta will play against Japan," said Passarella, a member of
champion team which won the trophy in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Batistuta, or "Batigol" for nickname, is the top Argentine scorer
with 38 goals and his fitness would be the key to success here.
</P>
<P>
Another striker to pound the Japanese defence on Sunday will be
nimble dribbler Ariel Ortega, known in his hometown as "Little
Donkey."
</P>
<P>
On the other side, Japan which qualified for the finals for the
first time after 44 years of attempt, would have an up-hill battle
relying on the talents of Masashi Nakayama.
</P>
<P>
Nakayama, scorer of an incredible four successive hat-tricks for
Jubilo Iwata in the J-League this spring, will be fed ammunitions from
a Japanese midfield organized by 21-year-old Hidetoshi Nakata.
</P>
<P>
But coach Takeshi Okada's main injury concern is experienced
defender and skipper Masami Ihara, who also suffered from an ankle
trouble and is expected to recover in time.
</P>
<P>
Okada knows that a lengthy horror story will be shown before the
Japanese goal if the team's defence crumbles amid blasts from a much
stronger Argentine offence but he would have no choice but fielding a
mixture of veterans and new faces.
</P>
<P>
The lack of crowd support in the Stade Municipal will be another
problem as thousands of Japanese fans arrived in France only to find
their travel agencies could not provide tickets.
</P>
<P>
The ticketless Japanese supporters will only be able to watch the
game live on a giant screen at the 5,000-seat Palais des Sports here,
arranged as an emergency measure by the local government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
