<HEADLINE> Gas Pipeline Salvage Work Begins in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The full-fledged salvage operation
for a 4.8-kilometer gas pipeline that collapsed Tuesday started
Saturday, press reports said.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline was anchored underneath the cantilever slab of the
Jamuna Multipurpose Bridge in Tangail district, 80 kilometers
northwest of Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
The bridge, the longest in Bangladesh and 11th longest in the
world, is being built at a cost of 900 million U.S. dollars. It
has been scheduled to be inaugurated on June 23.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place early Thursday when water ran through
the pipeline for leakage testing. Armymen have been sent to the
bridge site to re-install the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
The amount of loss in the crash was initially estimated at 90
million taka (about 1.96 million U.S. dollars), according to site
engineers and experts.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Hyundai Company, contractor for the bridge, and
Gas Transmission Company of Petrobangla (Bangladesh) were
responsible for the laying of the gas pipeline along the bridge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
