<HEADLINE> . mee061302hke -- Egypt, Libya Deny Report of Attack on Gaddafi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian and Libyan officials have
denied a report that Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi had been injured
in a failed attempt on his life.
</P>
<P>
The official Libyan news agency JANA Friday described the report of
an assassination attempt as "lies and vile allegation."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Egyptian Middle East News Agency's Arabic service
quoted an unnamed senior Egyptian security source as denying
Thursday's media report.
</P>
<P>
"The report is baseless and could be aimed at harming the firm
fraternal ties between the two brotherly countries and their
developing integration," the source said.
</P>
<P>
A foreign news agency report quoted travellers arriving in the
northwestern Egyptian town of Marsa Matrouh as saying Gaddafi had
scrapped a visit to Egypt earlier this month because of an attack in
the Mediterranean city of Benghazi in which he was slightly wounded
and many of his bodyguards were hurt.
</P>
<P>
Tripoli-based diplomats said on Thursday they had heard nothing
about any such attack, according to the Egyptian Mail daily Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan leader has suspended his week-long visit to Egypt slated
early this month, without giving reasons. But Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak told reporters this week that Gaddafi has a mild tonsil and is
expected to make the trip in 10 to 15 days. 
</P>
