<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TAZARA Managing Director Reinstated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Kingstone Mkandawire, suspended
managing director of the Tanzanian-Zambian railway (TAZARA) has
been reinstated after intervention of the Zambian government.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Saturday quoted Transport and Communications
Minister Anosh Chipawa as saying in Ndola, northern Zambia Friday
that he has instructed his permanent secretary to write to the
Tanzanian minister concerned declaring the suspension null and
void.
</P>
<P>
Mkandawire was suspended last week by the Tanzanian government
for alleged mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
Chipawa said the Tanzanian authorities did not consult the
Zambian government when taking the action.
</P>
<P>
He said it is legally the responsibility of the Zambian
government to employ the managing director and by the same token
to suspend or fire the director if any allegations against the
director are proven true.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania employs the deputy managing director of the
1,860-kilometer railway built by Chinese 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Chipawa said a board meeting will be held in Tanzania next
week to discuss a lot of issues including Mkandawire's case.
</P>
<P>
He said that ever since Mkandawire, who was a former Zambia
railway general manager for the northern region, was employed,
TAZARA's operations have improved a lot.
</P>
<P>
"He is very efficient and we don't know his weaknesses and if
the allegations are proved true then Zambia will take action," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania accused Mkandawire of spending money lavishly on
unworthwhile projects, making irrelevant trips, administer the
company with an iron fist and practising nepotism.
</P>
<P>
Mkandawire took over from another Zambian in a major shake-up
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
