<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Teenager Confesses to Killing 11 Family  Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 13 (Xinhua) -- A 19-year-old student has confessed to
the murder of 12 people, including his parents, nine of his family
members and one friend, in the most horrifying crime in the history of
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian police declared here late Friday night that Sa'eed Amin
Qashash confessed to the killings at his house in Bnyat neighborhood,
south of Amman, on Wednesday, saying his father had pressed him too
had over passing his high school examinations.
</P>
<P>
Amman police chief Brigadier Hisham Ensour told Jordan's official
media that the 12 bodies of those killed were recovered from the
basement of Qashash's family's two-storey building Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Qashash failed to pass his final examinations at high school in
1997, expected to fail again this year and thus decided to kill his
family members "because they threatened to kick him out of the house"
if he failed again, Ensour quoted Qashash as telling the
investigators.
</P>
<P>
Qashash told the police that he had stolen his father's pistol
one week before the crime date and hid it in his room.
</P>
<P>
The boy killed the victims one after another, put all the bodies
in the basement and sealed its door and windows with bricks and
cement, according to the police statement.
</P>
<P>
Later, the teenager submitted himself to the police, confessed to
the murders and handed over the weapon he used.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's serial killing has been the worst one of its kind in
Jordan, according to the police.
</P>
<P>
At high schools in Jordan, one has to pass the final examinations
before he can get a graduation diploma and then take the test for
college entranced. About 10 per cent of the high school students fail
in their final examinations each year, according to official figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
