<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT, June 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South Africa's currency Rand sank to a new
record low against the U.S. Dollar Friday despite a Reserve Bank
move to shore up local markets by cutting the repo rate to 17
percent from 17.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In late trade the Rand was at 5.3 to the Dollar, a loss of 44
cents in the year, after briefly touching a low of 5.34. At its
strongest level Friday, it was 5.225, local media reported
Saturday. (SAfrica-Rand)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HARARE -- Anglo American Zimbabwe Company has commissioned a
new gold mine in Nkayi of west Zimbabwe, The Herald daily reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Production at the gold mine, the company's second largest one
in the country, whose present capacity is 30,000 ounces of gold
per month, is expected to rise to 40,000 ounces a month.
</P>
<P>
Anglo American was planning to become the pre-eminent producer
of gold in Zimbabwe, with a target of some 300,000 ounces to 10
tons per annum in the next millennium. (ZIMBABWE-New Gold Mine)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- President Bill Clinton of the United States on
Friday extended the current bans on offshore oil drilling in
California and most of America's other coastal states for 10 more
years to help improve the ocean's health.
</P>
<P>
The ban, which continues a previous 10-year moratorium signed
by President George Bush in 1990, prohibits any new oil and gas
drilling in federal waters off California, Oregon, Washington,
southwest Florida, New England, southern Alaska and the
mid-Atlantic. (US-Clinton-Ocean)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KATHMANDU -- Six students succumbed to heatwave in the past few
days in western Nepal, The Kathmandu Post reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In Kapilvastu district, the six students died on June 8,
forcing the authorities to declare earlier starting of the summer
vacation for schools.
</P>
<P>
In neighboring Rupandehi district, the mercury hit a record 45
degree Celsius, the English-language daily said. (Nepal-Heatwave)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- The Colombo municipal Council (CMC) has taken
measures to prevent the spreading of cholera in the city after
four cholera positive cases were reported there, CMC sources said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Although cholera cases have been reported from different parts
of the country, the capital city has been free from cholera for
the last six months due to strict measures and constant
surveillance carried out by the CMC, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
From January 1 to June 10 this year, over 300 cholera cases had
 been reported from all parts of the country. (SriLanka-Cholera)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand's Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan urged
ASEAN to review its "non-interference" policy so as to play a more
constructive role in preventing controversies with regional
implications.
</P>
<P>
He said the "non-interference" principle of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) should not mean that ASEAN
countries should turn a blind eye to the plight of their
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"Lending assistance in time of need even on domestic affairs
should not be interpreted as interference in internal affairs,"
said Surin, quoted by Saturday's Nation newspaper.
(Thailand-ASEAN) 
