<HEADLINE> Firm Launched to Serve Foreign Labor in Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia has set up its first
company to handle problems concerning the recruitment of foreign
workers, who take a chunk share of the country's labor force.
</P>
<P>
Al-Suleiman &AMP; Al-Suwaid Manpower Service Company, based in Riyadh,
will pay visa fees and return tickets of expatriate workers while
adopting an insurance scheme, according to Saudi newspaper Arab News
available here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Muhammad AL-Suleiman, co-founder of the company, said they intend
to help resolve problems facing private recruitment offices while
recruiting manpower from certain countries.
</P>
<P>
He said about 30 percent of housemaids and servants in Saudi Arabia
come from Sri Lanka. About 35 percent of them do not complete their
contract period, incurring losses on the recruiting offices.
</P>
<P>
Al-Suleiman estimated the losses being suffered by local offices at
about 4,300 U.S. dollars for each visa as no guarantees are given to
secure their rights from the expatriates' side.
</P>
<P>
About Al-Hamoud, director general of Al-Hamoud Recruit Office,
described the new company as a "first step" in the way of promoting
recruitment services. "The market needs such a company to guarantee
the rights of private recruitment offices," he said.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has a population of 18 million, including 6 million
foreign. Only 7 percent of workers in private sector are nationals.
</P>
</TEXT>
