<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Province Doing Forestry Work Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 13 (Xinhua) -- China's Guangdong Province is
doing more to develop forestry resources overseas, and recently
signed a letter of intent with Malaysia to help it reproduce rare
species of trees, Forestry Department sources say.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong began this cooperation overseas early in 1984 when it
reached an agreement with Macao on nearly 170 hectares of forest
area for ring roads. The project was completed in 1988, and gave
Guangdong about 4.39 million Hong Kong dollars.
</P>
<P>
Another effort was by the Guangdong Yuzhu Forestry Products
Group and a Hong Kong company in 1995 to cultivate 150,000
hectares of tropical forest and 57 million cubic meters of timber
reserves in Surinam.
</P>
<P>
The two companies have now developed 5,000 cubic meters of
timber, and shipped them back to China for use.
</P>
<P>
The province is known for its forestry technology and has begun
to export equipment and technology for forestry applications. The
provincial Academy of Forestry Science reached an agreement in
1994 with Vietnam's Ho Chi Minh City on exporting saplings of fine
and helping plant eucalyptus and other trees.
</P>
<P>
The province has more than a dozen forestry cooperation
projects overseas, sources say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
