<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Helps Zambia's Copper Mines to Pay off Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has injected 80
million U.S. Dollars in Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM)
in the past month to help the mines pay off its international and
local debt prior to the privatization of its assets.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Saturday quoted Mines Minister Syamukayumbu
Syamujaye as saying Friday that 50 million Dollars was released
last month while another 30 million Dollars has recently been
released to help ZCCM decongest its debt stock as negotiations
for its privatization continue.
</P>
<P>
The new debt that is being accrued by ZCCM which used to cover
more than 90 percent of the country's foreign exchange earnings
will have to be included in the value for which the mines will
eventually be sold, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the continued accrual of debt by the state-owned
conglomerate is of concern to the government and it is therefore
important that its assets are sold off as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Syamujaye announced that the Nkana and Nchanga mines, two
largest ones registering about 65 percent of ZCCM's copper
production, are now scheduled to be sold off by the end of July
after the failure of the initial privatization talks with the
Kafue Consortium, while the remaining assets of ZCCM will be sold
off by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Kafue Consortium, the sole bidders for ZCCM's Nkana and
Nchanga mines, has finally collapsed following the decision by
its members to abandon the project after 16-month long unfruitful
negotiations with the Zambian government.
</P>
<P>
Mining analysts here, however, feel that mines should be
quickly disposed of because the mines' current one million
Dollars per day operational costs has become a strain on the
national revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
