<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore to Promote Manufacturing Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Singapore will make great
efforts to develop manufacturing services in a bid to maintain the
manufacturing industry as a key pillar in the economy, a senior
official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"To maintain the primacy of manufacturing in Singapore, we have
to promote manufacturing services," Second Minister for Trade &AMP;
Industry and Minister for Information &AMP; the Arts George Yeo said
at the official opening of Siemens Matsushita's components PTE
LTD, a new facility designed to produce Surface Acoustic Wave
filters for the telecommunication industry.
</P>
<P>
Siemens is now the largest German investor which employs 3,200
people here. The Matsushita Electric Industrial of Japan has 10
operations and employs more than 12,000 workers in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Describing manufacturing and services as the country's "two
engines of growth," the minister said the Economic and Development
Board has launched a program called Industry 21, which targets a
25 percent of manufacturing's share in GDP by 2010 and a 6 percent
share of manufacturing services in GDP in the period which will
double the figure of 3 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the growing importance of manufacturing services
in developing a knowledge-based economy, he said: "We will no
longer be able to compete in simple assembly line production. We
must instead compete on research and development, product design,
product development, process engineering, testing services, market
research and so on."
</P>
<P>
Since Singapore launched in 1993 a manufacturing-promoting
program called Manufacturing 2000. The city-country has pursued a
policy to build up manufacturing as a key pillar of its economy
and as a result manufacturing now contributes about 23 percent of
its GDP and has an employment share of about 23 percent, according
to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the country is facing new emerging challenges as
the new century is nearing, the minister said: "Our strategy must
therefore be to continue moving up the value chain and finding new
ways to add value in Manufacturing."
</P>
<P>
Of the 15,000 job to be created each year, he said, at least
two-thirds should be for knowledge and skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
The minister affirmed that Singapore will strive to diversify
its economy to a greater extent, to build up world-class
capabilities, to promote a culture of innovation, to enhance
continuing education and training and to strengthen links with all
parts of the world so as to make the Industry 21 program a
success. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Kenyan Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Kenyan newspapers Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The Ethiopian mountain town of Adigrat was almost deserted
Friday after a bombing raid by Eritrea Thursday, which residents
said left at least four dead and 30 wounded.
</P>
<P>
Daily Nation:
</P>
<P>
-- Despite its declared neutrality, Djibouti is closely
involved in the war between its neighbors Eritrea and Ethiopia,
by reason especially of its virtual monopoly on supplies to the
latter country.
</P>
<P>
-- Ugandan rebels of the Lords Resistance Amy have attacked
northern Otwal subcounty, Apac district and abducted over 30
people.
</P>
<P>
East African Standard:
</P>
<P>
-- Burundi's presidency has named two vice-presidents,
including an ethnic Hutu leader of the main opposition party, as
part of a reform package designed to ease tension in the central
African country. 
</P>
