<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces Initiatives to Improve Oceans' Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 12 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton of the
United States on Friday extended the current bans on offshore oil
drilling in California and most of America's other coastal states
for 10 more years to help improve the ocean's health.
</P>
<P>
Oil spills from offshore drilling can spoil the coasts, causing
not just the death of marine life, but the destruction of the
fragile ecosystem, said the president on the closing day of the
country's first national ocean conference.
</P>
<P>
The president had been seeking a balance between industry needs
and the environment, his aides said.
</P>
<P>
The ban, which continues a previous 10-year moratorium signed
by President George Bush in 1990, prohibits any new oil and gas
drilling in federal waters off California, Oregon, Washington,
southwest Florida, New England, southern Alaska and the
mid-Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
There are 28 oil platforms in the waters along California's
coastline, all built between late 1950s and early 1080s. They
account for about four percent of America's yearly oil production.
</P>
<P>
Other initiatives include a ban on the sale and import of
Atlantic swordfish weighing less than 33 pounds, and an
800-million-dollar plan to deepen the country's harbors.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 scientists, policymakers, environmentalists and
business leaders attended the conference in Monterey, California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Gold Mine Commissioned in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Anglo American Zimbabwe Company
has commissioned a new gold mine in Nkayi of west Zimbabwe, The
Herald daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Production at the gold mine, the company's second largest one
in the country, whose present capacity is 30,000 ounces of gold
per month, is expected to rise to 40,000 ounces a month.
</P>
<P>
Anglo American was planning to become the pre-eminent producer
of gold in Zimbabwe, with a target of some 300,000 ounces to 10
tons per annum in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony Friday, Nicky Oppenheimer,
deputy chairman of Anglo American Corporation of South Africa,
said, "We need to recognize that the world is shrinking in size
as communication becomes easier, finance becomes more mobile and
trade barriers around the world begin to fall."
</P>
<P>
"To meet these challenges, we as a country and a corporation
need to make the most of our advantages and minii our
disadvantages as we compete in the global playing field," he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Oppenheimer, the new mine was a show of the
confidence they had in Zimbabwe's economy. He urged governments
in the southern African region to continue improving the
investment climates in their countries.
</P>
<P>
Anglo American Corporation operates a number of mines in
Zimbabwe while it has announced plans to open a 77-million-U.S.
Dollars platinum mine, which is the country's second largest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
