<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Troops Clash With Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June (Xinhua) -- Philippine government troops and Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) rebels clashed Friday in Buldon,
Maguindanao, the Southern Philippines, but so far no casualties
have been reported.
</P>
<P>
The official Philippine News Agency reported Saturday that the
incident was the latest in the series of sporadic encounters in
the area though the government and the MILF signed a cessation of
hostilities agreement last July.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that Friday's fighting occurred at the time the
Quick Reaction Team (QRT), a peace body formed by the government
and MILF to look into violations of the ceasefire agreement, was
investigating related incidents in the provinces of Sultan Kudarat
and Zamboanga del Sur.
</P>
<P>
Speaking over a radio station, Al Haj. Murad, deputy MILF
military chief, claimed that government troops belonging to the
39th Infantry Battalion (IB) fired 10 rounds of 105 mm howitzers
at their perimeter defense in Camp Abubakar while pursuing a group
of armed men in the area.
</P>
<P>
Murad said they were forced to fire back at the soldiers with a
number of 81 and 60 mm mortar shells "as Abubakar was threatened."
</P>
<P>
The exchange of fires lasted one hour, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the group being pursued by the 39th IB were bandits
responsible for the series of cattle rustlings in the area and not
members of the MILF.
</P>
<P>
"It so happened that they (bandits) ran towards our direction
leading soldiers to suspect they were MILFs," the rebel leader
explained.
</P>
<P>
Murad vowed to include and bring up the recent incident to the
government - MILF peace panel during their next meeting later this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
