<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Per Capita Income Reaches 264.8 Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's per capita income in
the July 1997-June 1998 fiscal year stands at 12,181 taka (about
264.8 U.S. dollars), marking a 7.72 percent rise over the previous
fiscal year, the United News of Bangladesh (UNB) reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In the 1996-97 fiscal year, per capita income was 11,288 taka
(about 245.4 dollars), 5.9 percent higher than that of the
previous fiscal year, the report quoted the Economic Survey of
Bangladesh 1998 as saying.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that the gross domestic product (GDP) in the
current fiscal year was 1,540.92 billion taka (about 33.5 billion
dollars), with a growth rate of 9.83 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the current fiscal year, the growth rate of the agricultural
sector was 3.1 percent while that of the industrial sector was 7.3
percent, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
The industrial growth rates included manufacturing 8.1 percent,
medium and large industries 10.1, small industries 4.2 percent,
energy, gas, water and sanitary 5.8 and construction 6.2 percent,
the survey stated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Confident of Hosting Asian Games in 2006 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is confident of
hosting the 2006 Asian Games based on existing facilities and
organization skills of the Commonwealth Games in September, a
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Youth and Sports Minister Muhyiddin Yassin said the government
had given the green light to the Olympic Council of Malaysia
(OCM) to make the official bid for the 2006 Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
"I understand that India and Syria are among those interested
but we are confident of being selected based on our track record,"
he was quoted as saying in the New Straits Times newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The minister added: "To land the host job, the success of the
Commonwealth Games is vital as it will reflect further our
organizational skills."
</P>
<P>
OCM general secretary Sieh Kok Chi said that the infrastructure
for the Commonwealth Games would not require any upgrading if
Malaysia is to host the 2006 games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
