<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 32-Year-Old Panda Critically Ill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, June 13 (Xinhua) -- One of the three eldest giant
pandas in China, 32-year-old Zhuzhu, became critically ill in
southwest China's Guiyang Province and doctors from hospitals are
drafting measures for rescuing the panda.
</P>
<P>
The male giant panda caught a cold on June 7. He had a running
nose and was even reluctant to take his most favorite food --
bamboo and other food.
</P>
<P>
The Guiyang Qianling Park Zoo, where the panda is housed, has
established an emergency group to rescue the aged and weak
panda. The zoo has contacted Chengdu Panda Base where Zhuzhu came
from to seek help.
</P>
<P>
The panda has received injections and infusion of fluid. But,
it did not respond to the treatment well and only had a small
amount of urine after massage in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
Five experts on respiratory tract diseases, cardiovascular
diseases and kidney diseases from Guiyang Medical College have
made an overall health check-up for the sick panda.
</P>
<P>
Doctors said Zhuzhu's cold was caused by a sudden drop of
temperature in Guiyang, the provincial capital city.
</P>
<P>
They said the panda is too old and the functions of its organs
fail to operate normally, adding Zhuzhu's life is in danger if its
conditions do not make a turn for the better.
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, a wild giant panda can only live for 16
years, while the average age of giant pandas in zoos is 25 years.
</P>
<P>
The eldest giant panda in China is 36-year-old Dudu at Wuhan
Zoo in central China's Hubei Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahathir: Malaysia Welcomes FDIs, Not Hot money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia welcomes more
foreign direct investments (FDIs), but not "hot money" or
speculative funds, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has regarded genuine foreign direct investors as
permanent contributors to Malaysia's industrial development, he
said at the opening of a cement factory in Bukit Sagu near
Kuantan, about 260 kilometers east from here.
</P>
<P>
"We always treat them as special guests of the country. They
are different from the other kind of investors, especially on the
stock market, who come and go," he was quoted by the Malaysian
national news agency Bernama as saying.
</P>
<P>
"As for hot money, keep it hot elsewhere," Mahathir said,
adding "I know that will affect the recovery of the economy but I
want a healthy economic recovery. We do not want a recovery that
is impermanent."
</P>
<P>
He said those who invested in the stock market were not
permanent investors.
</P>
<P>
However, he said: "They are still welcome provided they invest
for the dividends."
</P>
<P>
He said "Hot money" investors had dumped their shares when
prices were riding high to gain hefty profits and this had had a
damaging effect on local companies, local investors and the
country.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir assured that all necessary incentives would be
provided for foreign direct investors, but hot money is not what
Malaysia welcome.
</P>
<P>
He said that "for the foreign direct investors, we are prepared
to go out of the way to welcome them. Their contribution towards
Malaysia's industrial development is very valuable."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the country was now facing problems because of
the depreciation of the ringgit and the fall in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
He said that when "hot money" wove in and out of the stock
market, it would leave a trail of destruction.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir was of the view that foreigners must realize that
investments in the country must benefit not only them but the host
country as well.
</P>
<P>
He said although the country had stipulated that foreign
interests could take up to 30 percent equity in local companies,
some of them had even exceeded 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
"There is no way we can track them because that is something
that comes very fast. And when they dump the shares to take up
capital gains, local shareholders are left to bear the costs," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
