<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka To Ban Advertisements of Alcohol, Tobacco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's state media including
print media will be banned from carrying advertisements of alcohol
and tobacco from January 1, next year, according to media ministry
sources here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said President Chandrika Kumaratunga has directed
the ministry to instruct all state media including print media
not to accept advertisements of alcohol and tobacco from January
1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The president said in a letter to Media Minister Mangala
Samaraweera that "my attention has been drawn to the promotion of
alcohol and tobacco use via the media, through advertising, and
through portrayals in teledramas. I have been informed that such
promotion is becoming more common in recent months especially in
the electronic media, both in government owned and privately owned
radio and television channels."
</P>
<P>
There is an unacceptable situation in the country, where the
democratic and open-minded approach of the government towards the
media is being used to achieve commercial gains by promoting
products that are known to cause tremendous social, economic and
health harm in the country, the president said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
