<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's 1st Off-Shore Gasfield Goes into Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's first off-shore
gasfield, Sangu Gasfield, on Friday went into commercial
production and started delivering gas to the national gas grid,
according to reports reaching here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Located in the Bay of Bengal, the gasfield has been developed
with a total cost of about 300 million U.S. dollars by the
Scotland-based Cairn Energy PLC along with the U.S. Halliburton
and the British-based Shell companies, having 56.25, 25 and 18.75
percent shares respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Cairn Energy and Shell struck the gas reserve at Sangu,
some 5 kilometers off the port city of Chittagong, in February
1996 under a production-sharing contract for the hydrocarbon block
16 of the country.
</P>
<P>
The gasfield is anticipated to produce up to 160 million
standard cubic feet of gas per day during the first 6 to 9 months
and will then stabilize at around 200 million standard cubic feet
of gas per day in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
The gasfield is expected to deliver 20 percent of Bangladesh's
gas production, the reports added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
