<HEADLINE> Thailand's Exports Continue to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports for May showed
a continued fall for the third consecutive month or a 2.98 percent
drop from the month before, the Customs Department said.
</P>
<P>
The department's Director General Somchainuk Engtrakul said in
a statement received on Saturday that Thailand's exports in May
were worth only 164 billion baht (4.268 billion U.S. dollars), 5
billion baht (125 million dollars) less than April.
</P>
<P>
The 10 exported items which show high potential include
computers, electrical appliances, garments, integrated circuits,
rubber and canned seafood. Rice, jewelry and shrimps showed a
sharp drop.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thailand has benefited from a drop in imports. In
May, imports were valued at 129 billion baht (3.22 billion
dollars), compared with 144 billion baht (3.6 billion dollars) a
month earlier. In dollar terms, the fall was 8.54 percent, while
in baht it was 10.12 percent.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, the Customs Department's revenue had dropped due
to lower imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
