<HEADLINE> Thai Academics Urged to Help Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Thai Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanahaeminda said Friday night that he has asked academics in
the country to propose measures to immunize the Thai economy
against global fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said after meeting with 30 top academics that he had
given them the job as "homework".
</P>
<P>
A special session was held Friday night to allow an exchange of
view-points between the government and academics on how to tackle
the economic crisis hitting Thailand and how to save the country
from a further slump.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said he had taken seven to eight pages of notes on ideas
proposed by the academics and would urgently study them.
</P>
<P>
One of the proposals raised during the meeting was that the
government adopt a more selective policy on saving particular
industries from the crisis instead of desperately trying to keep
all of them afloat.
</P>
<P>
"Under the current situation, the government has to choose
which particular industries it will help sustain. It cannot save
all of them," Somkiat Osotspa, a lecturer from Chulalongkorn
University, said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The academics called on the government to prepare to take
action to cope with a further downturn of the Thai economy in the
next few months.
</P>
<P>
Among the measures the government was advised to take is debt
restructuring, with the help of both the public and private
sectors, according to a TV report Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It was also proposed that the government formulate social
measures to inject monetary support into the rural sector to help
strengthen the economy domestically.
</P>
<P>
The academics also cautioned that the government must try all
means to sustain the baht's stability and curb inflation to a
level not too far above 10 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
