<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai FM Calls for Review of ASEAN's Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan urged ASEAN to review its "non-interference" policy so as
to play a more constructive role in preventing controversies with
regional implications.
</P>
<P>
He said the "non-interference" principle of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) should not mean that ASEAN
countries should turn a blind eye to the plight of their
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"Lending assistance in time of need even on domestic affairs
should not be interpreted as interference in internal affairs,"
said Surin, quoted by Saturday's Nation newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The minister was speaking on Friday at a seminar held to
commemorate the 49th anniversary of the Political Science
Department at Thammasat University in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"Perhaps it is time for ASEAN's cherished non-intervention
principle to be modified," Surin said.
</P>
<P>
"Non-interference does not mean that we cannot espouse the
values of our own society, although, of course, we should not try
to impose them on others," he said.
</P>
<P>
When a matter of domestic concern poses a threat to regional
stability, a dose of peer pressure or friendly advice can be
helpful," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said if there was a consensus among the group's members on
the type of situation warranting constructive intervention, the
process should become easier.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that Thailand has expressed interest in
the review of ASEAN's non-intervention principle, which had been
criticized as a pretext for ASEAN not to help end conflicts in
member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Send More Workers Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government called
on recruitment agencies around the country to make a serious
effort to reduce the unemployment problem by sending more workers
abroad, reported The Indonesian Observer Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The government's efforts to curb unemployment could succeed if
recruitment agencies could find more jobs for Indonesians abroad,
director of the country's Recruitment Companies Association Munir
Ahmad said.
</P>
<P>
If more Indonesians are sent to work in other countries, he
said, the amount of foreign revenue coming into the country will
increase substantially.
</P>
<P>
But most recruitment agencies told the newspaper that they
won't be able to help until the government puts an end to the
monopolies controlled by certain agencies.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government failed to meet its target of sending
2.5 million Indonesian workers abroad during the sixth Five-Year
Development Plan (1993-97).
</P>
<P>
As the economic crisis deepens, many Indonesians are now unable
to come up with the funds needed to travel abroad for work.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Manpower Ministry has provided 77.5 billion
rupiah (about 6 million U.S. dollars) for an intensive labor
program that aims to provide employment for those rendered jobless
by the financial crisis and recent riots in Jakarta and other
cities.
</P>
<P>
According to the People's Welfare/Poverty Eradication Ministry,
if the economic crisis persists, the number of people living below
the poverty line in the country is expected to reach 30 million.
</P>
<P>
Before the economic crisis began in mid-1997, only 22 million
of Indonesia's 202 million people were living below the poverty
line.
</P>
<P>
The number of poor people in Central Jakarta alone has
increased drastically from 150,000 in 1997 to 300,000 in 1998.
That means about 25 percent of Central Jakarta's 1.2 million
people are now poor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
