<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Tightens Sanctions on Angola's UNITA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
adopted a resolution Friday to impose further sanctions on
Angola's National Union for the Total Independent of Angola
(UNITA) for its failure to fully implement peace obligations.
</P>
<P>
The sanction measures include freezing of funds and financial
resources of UNITA as an organization or of its senior officials
or immediate families and prevention of all official contacts with
the UNITA leadership.
</P>
<P>
They also include prohibiting anyone from importing diamonds
without a certificate of origin from the Angolan government, and
prohibiting the sale of mining equipment and motorized vehicles or
water transportation services to areas the government does not
control.
</P>
<P>
The measures will come into force on June 25 unless the
Security Council decides on the basis of a report by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan that UNITA has fully complied by June
23 with all its relevant obligations.
</P>
<P>
The new sanctions follow those imposed last year to curb
travels by senior UNITA officials and the closing of UNITA offices
abroad.
</P>
<P>
Council members criticized UNITA for delaying in handing over
four regions it controls to the national unity government and
failing to demobilizing its fighters as requested by the 1994
Lusaka Protocol and for attacking government officials and U.N.
personnel.
</P>
<P>
Taking the floor at the Council consultations, Chinese
Ambassador Shen Guofang urged UNITA to heed the demands of the
Angolan people and the international community to completely
comply with its obligations and to achieve national reconciliation
together with the Angolan government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
