<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Funds Not Enough If Crisis Spreads: IMF Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) may not be able to provide enough funds if the monetary
crisis which has gripped Southeast Asia and East Asia continued to
spread, local press Saturday quoted an IMF official as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe some time in the future, the funds from IMF would not be
sufficient," IMF advisor for the Indonesian government Prabhakar
Narvekar said.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Indonesia's Coordinating Minister for
Economy, Finance and Industry Ginandjar Kartasasmita here Friday,
Narvekar said the fund for the restoration of the Indonesian
economy will have to be sought by the IMF from its member
countries within the shortest possible time.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the IMF must also treat other equally
important "patients" besides Indonesia, he added.
</P>
<P>
The IMF promised last October to provide 10 billion U.S.
dollars of the 43 billion U.S. dollar bailout fund which the
agency brokered to bail out Indonesia's ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
It initially agreed to disburse the bailout money in 3 billion
U.S. dollar tranches, to make sure that Indonesia remains
committed to the agreed reforms.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia received the first installment of 3 billion U.S.
dollars in November, but the second disbursement of 3 billion U.S.
dollars was delayed and divided into three monthly installments,
each amounting to one billion U.S. dollars, following a failed
attempt by the government to implement the promised reforms.
</P>
<P>
The second one billion U.S. dollar payment, due this month,
will likely be made only next month.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has sent a review team, led by IMF Asia Pacific
director Hubert Neiss, to review Indonesia's economic reform
programs before the IMF board of directors makes a decision
whether to disburse the second one billion U.S. dollar payment.
</P>
<P>
Ginandjar expected that the IMF team will finish making its
evaluation later this month so that the IMF can release the funds
desperately needed by Indonesia early next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
