<HEADLINE> Old Friend Becomes Part of China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese people view Clark Johnson,
who most often puffs on a big cigar and sports a fashionable tie,
as a typical American businessman.
</P>
<P>
However, he is much more than simply a successful businessman
in China and on Thursday received the Marco Polo Award, one of the
highest honors the Chinese Government grants to
foreigners. Johnson received the award for his outstanding
contributions to trade and personnel exchanges between the United
States and China.
</P>
<P>
Pier 1 Imports, Johnson's U.S.-based company, has imported
Chinese products valued at over two billion US dollars and has
sponsored experts recruited by Volunteers of America to assist
China's economic development over the years.
</P>
<P>
"We've been here for so long that we are now a part of
it," said Johnson, chairman and CEO of the Texas-based speciality
retail company.
</P>
<P>
Pier 1 Imports initiated business with China in 1975. The
company weathered the ups and downs of the Sino-US relations over
past decades and has never stopped dealing with China.
</P>
<P>
"I think that economic exchanges between the two countries are
far removed from political issues," said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
"The business community in the United States recognizes that
trade and economic relations are of equal importance to the
interests of both countries,
</P>
<P>
"We've worked hard to overcome some of the noise in political
relations (with China)," according to Johnson.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that President Clinton's upcoming visit to
China will have the same important impact on the Chinese people as
Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to the U.S. last fall had on
American citizens.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that strengthening the Sino-U.S. strategic
partnership will create a more positive situation for the Chinese
market and will in turn provide more business opportunities for
U.S. companies in China.
</P>
<P>
Pier 1 Imports currently has 155 suppliers in China, including
a large number of state-owned enterprises. The company regularly
invites personnel from Chinese factories to visit its chain stores
around the world in order to help them gain a greater
understanding of the needs of customers and learn more about the
international market. Related efforts are designed to help Chinese
factories improve competitiveness of their products.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, who has traveled to almost every part of China, said
the company often purchases woven products from one particular
village. He said that seeing how grandmothers, mothers and
children in the village work together for a prosperous future
makes him feel he has made a truly beneficial contribution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Friend Becomes Part of China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He expressed his belief that China has witnessed more changes
over the past more than 10 years than recorded over past 1,000 years
combined.
</P>
<P>
The company had to search for suppliers when first arriving in
China. Now, however, many Chinese enterprises approach the company
which has gained fame throughout China.
</P>
<P>
Johnson said the Chinese Government has done an excellent job
in effort to encourage enterprises to increase exports.
</P>
<P>
His company has benefited greatly from trade with China. Its
imports of furniture, utensils for both dining and entertainment,
bedroom and bathroom accessories, and handmade arts and crafts
from China have increased at an annual rate and now account for 15
percent growth rate for the companies global sales. Imports of
metal furniture have grown by over 100 percent annually in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
China is the company's largest supplier, with Chinese products
accounting for 32 percent of total sales. Chinese merchandise have
entered homes in many other countries through the company's 770
chain stores worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Johnson said Chinese merchandise have a excellent reputation
for good quality and Chinese workers are known for their
entrepreneurship and ability to learn quickly. Chinese factories
adapt quickly in terms of producing merchandise in demand on the
international market.
</P>
<P>
He cited the aforementioned factors as the reason he constantly
seeks new sources of supply in China. Pier 1 Imports also plans to
open chain stores in China.
</P>
<P>
He said that the financial crisis in Southeast Asia will not
affect the company's long-term strategy to expand operations in
China.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the U.S. business community strongly
supports President Clinton's move to extend the Most Favored
Nation trade status to China and expressed hope that the issue of
China's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO) will be
resolved soon.
</P>
<P>
He said President Clinton was "smart" to ensure his
administration took concrete steps to improve US-Sino relations
and comprehensively strengthen bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese people will never forget friends who help them. I
believe this partnership will continue to move forward," said
Johnson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
