<HEADLINE> Government Welcomes Defection of Khmer Rouge Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian Royal government
Saturday welcomed the defection of five high-ranking figures of
the Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
Sok An, a cabinet member, told Xinhua that the government is
sending a team on Saturday morning to Pailin to talk with the five
Khmer Rouge important members, the news of whose defection was
broadcast by Television of Kampuchea (TVK) on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
On the government stand on Ta Mok, Noun Chea and Khieu Samphan,
the three other Khmer Rouge important members, Sok An said that
they are hardliners and must be put on trial.
</P>
<P>
Television of Kampuchea interrupted the World Cup football
match broadcasting shortly before midnight Friday to announce the
defection by Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister of Khmer
Rouge Interim Government Chan Youran, Finance Minister Mak Ben,
Minister for Immigration En Sopheap, Labor Minister Kor Bum Heng
and Special Advisor to the Prime Minister Thiounn Thioeun.
</P>
<P>
It said that the five signed a statement in Pailin near
Cambodia-Thailand border Thursday, declaring they broke with the
Khmer Rouge on May 3.
</P>
<P>
The statement said in order to end the decades of civil war and
lingering unrest in Cambodia, they determined to break with the
Khmer Rouge hardliners Ta Mok and Nuon Chea and return to
Cambodian national community.
</P>
<P>
It also stated that they would accept the Constitutions of the
country and the Royal government and respect the important role of
King Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
The Khmer Rouge Interim Government was outlawed by the
Cambodian National Assembly (parliament) passed a bill in July
1994.
</P>
<P>
Under mounting pressures from both the inside and outside of
the organization, Khmer Rouge officials and soldiers kept
defecting to the government in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Ieng Sary, among many other Khmer Rouge important
members, led a big group of soldiers to surrender to the
government.
</P>
<P>
Almost all strongholds of the Khmer Rouge guerrilla group,
including Anlong Veng near the Cambodia-Thailand border, have
fallen into the hands of the government forces.
</P>
<P>
Former Khmer Rouge leader, Pol Pot, died of heart attack on
April 15 this year on a hill near Anlong Veng. 
</P>
</TEXT>
