<HEADLINE> Central America Defends Export Privileges in EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Central American countries
are trying to defend their export privileges in the European Union
(EU).
</P>
<P>
It is "an important factor in the creation of jobs in the
region," Costa Rican Chamber of Exporters President Antonio
Burgues said Friday, referring to the Generalized System of
Preferences that permits Central American countries to export
products worth more than 1.1 billion U.S. dollars to the EU market.
</P>
<P>
He said that these products generate 1.3 million direct and
indirect jobs in the non-traditional agricultural sector, and
enable 1.7 million people to work in the coffee sector.
</P>
<P>
A long list of Central American agricultural products are
allowed to enter the European Common Market duty-free, but the
regime expires on June 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the European Commission is preparing its
proposal of a new Generalized System of Preferences applicable to
Central American countries. 
</P>
