<HEADLINE> Canada Welcomes WTO's Ruling on Salmon Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Canada has welcomed the World Trade
Organization's (WTO) ruling on the Canada-Australia salmon dispute
which judges that Australia's ban on importing Canadian salmon is
inconsistent with its WTO obligations.
</P>
<P>
The ruling, made by the WTO's Dispute Settlement Body Friday,
requests Australia to bring its regulations on imports of fresh,
chilled and frozen salmon from Canada in conformity with WTO rules.
</P>
<P>
"This final ruling of the WTO has very clearly upheld Canada's
case," said Canadian International Trade Minister Minister Sergio
Marchi, "This also demonstrates that Canada's trade interests are
best defended through a system of fair and equitable rules."
</P>
<P>
Australia's ban was first introduced in 1975. After years of
unsuccessful bilateral efforts to resolve the dispute, the WTO
Dispute Settlement Body established a panel on April 10, 1997, at
Canada's request.
</P>
<P>
Australia still has the right to appeal the WTO ruling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
