<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Makes Efforts to Help Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government approved a law
Friday to help poor families with income support in
poverty-stricken areas for a two year trial period.
</P>
<P>
The law aims to keep low-income families above the poverty line
by providing them with a minimum income of 500,000 lire (about 285
U.S. dollars) a month.
</P>
<P>
The new income support scheme will be introduced on a trial
basis in a dozen pilot areas, mainly in the south, and is expected
to benefit about 15,000 to 20,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The cities and towns involved in the experiment will be decided
in the next 30 days. The decision will be made by the central and
regional governments on the basis of poverty statistics, Social
Solidarity Minister Livia Turco said.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want the measure to be confined to big cities, but
rather to focus on small and middle cities, especially in the
Mezzogiorno where 70 percent of the poor live," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Anyone benefiting from the plan will have to take part in job
training programs and other initiatives aimed at rehabilitating
the poor and marginalized, Turco said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
