<HEADLINE> Sino-French Semiconductor Firm Starts Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen STS Microelectronics
(STS), one of China's largest semiconductor integrated circuit
(IC) projects, went into official operation in the Shenzhen
Special Economic Zone (SEZ) Friday.
</P>
<P>
STS has been jointly established by French ST Microelectronics
(ST), a global semiconductor company, and the Shenzhen SEG Hi-Tech
Industrial Co. Ltd, a subsidiary of the Shenzhen Electronics Group
Co. Ltd (SEG) in south China's Guangdong Province, reported
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Located in the Futian Free Trade Zone of the SEZ, STS costed an
initial investment of 100 million U.S. dollars with ST having 60
percent of the stake.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture, which started trial operation in early 1997,
is engaged in assembling the semiconductor chips made by ST
plants in other countries and regions, testing a wide range of
semiconductor devices and designing Application Specific
Integrated Circuits.
</P>
<P>
Currently, it has an annual production capacity of 730 million
semiconductor ICs, which is expected to be expanded to one billion
pieces this year and two billion in 2000, according to Wang
Dianfu, chairman of SEG and STS.
</P>
<P>
"The financial troubles (in Asia) do not affect long-term
prospects in the region or our investment here," said Pasquale
Pistorio, ST's president and chief executive officer, adding that
STS, ST's first joint venture in China, would help his company
further integrate into this region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
