<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Council Issues Circular on Poverty Alleviation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The State Council has issued a
circular urging local governments to do a good job in poverty
relief this year.
</P>
<P>
In order to carry out the state program of eradicating poverty
in the rural areas by the year 2000, more than ten million people
should be provided with adequate food and clothes this year, the
circular notes.
</P>
<P>
Local governments in poor areas should continue to implement
the methods which have proved effective for poverty alleviation
and seek new and pioneering ways to complete the target for this
year.
</P>
<P>
The State Council has decided to appropriate a record 18.3
billion yuan (2.2 billion US dollars) of poverty relief funds this
year. Local governments should in turn exert conscientious efforts
to ensure supportive funds and make sure that the funds go to the
areas and people in need on time.
</P>
<P>
The money must be used well, and those misuse or embezzle such
funds will have their criminal responsibility investigated,
according to the circular.
</P>
<P>
Following a policy set by the national poverty alleviation and
development conference held in 1996, the economically booming
provinces and cities in the eastern part of the country should
continue to give assistance to the impoverished areas in the west,
the circular says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilians Leave Guinea-Bissau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian nationals have
left Guinea-Bissau because of the escalating military conflicts in
the small African country.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian media reported Friday that 60 Brazilians, half of
the total of Brazilian residents in Guinea-Bissau, have left the
west African country aboard a Portuguese ship bound to Senegal,
and the remaining 32 Brazilians have taken shelter in the
Brazilian Embassy in Guinea-Bissau.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian Foreign Ministry condemned the recent coup
attempt by the military against legally elected president and
called for immediate restoration of order in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian government is following with attention the
developments in the African country, formerly a Portuguese colony,
and maintains contacts with the governments of Portugal and France
to evacuate remaining Brazilian residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
