<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Top Khmer Rouge Members Defects to Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Five high-ranking figures of
the Khmer Rouge have defected to the Cambodian government,
Television of Kampuchea (TVK) reported on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
The report said the five signed a statement in Pailin near
Cambodia-Thailand border Thursday, declaring they broke with the
Khmer Rouge on May 3.
</P>
<P>
The five are Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister of
Khmer Rouge Interim Government Chan Youran, Finance Minister Mak
Ben, Minister for Immigration En Sopheap, Labor Minister Kor Bum
Heng and Special Advisor to the Prime Minister Thiounn
Thioeun.
</P>
<P>
The statement said in order to end the decades of civil war and
lingering unrest in Cambodia, they determined to break with the
Khmer Rouge hardliners Ta Mok and Nuon Chea and return to
Cambodian national community.
</P>
<P>
It also stated that they would accept the Constitutions of the
country and the Royal government and respect the important role of
King Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
The Khmer Rouge Interim Government was outlawed by the
Cambodian National Assembly (parliament) passed a bill in July
1994.
</P>
<P>
Under mounting pressures from both the inside and outside of the
organization, Khmer Rouge officials and soldiers kept defecting to
the government in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Ieng Sary, among many other Khmer Rouge important
members, led a big group of soldiers to surrender to the
government.
</P>
<P>
Almost all strongholds of the Khmer Rouge guerrilla group,
including Anlong Veng near the Cambodia-Thailand border, have
fallen into the hands of the government forces.
</P>
<P>
Former Khmer Rouge leader, Pol Pot, died of heart attack on
April 15 this year on a hill near Anlong Veng, the last stronghold
of the guerrilla group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maradona Receives Suspended Sentence for Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Former Argentine soccer Star
Diego Maradona was convicted on Friday of shooting journalists
with an air rifle in 1994 and received a suspended sentence of two
years and 10 months .
</P>
<P>
His lawyer, Hugo Wortman Jofre, said he would appeal. The
journalists injured by Maradona said they would also appeal
because they considered the suspended sentence too light.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors and the journalists' lawyers had sought four years
in jail for Maradona. In the Argentine legal system, any sentence
over three years must be served in prison.
</P>
<P>
Maradona's career has been marred in recent years by drug
scandals and short-lived comebacks. He was banned for 15 months
for taking cocaine while playing for the Napoli team in Italy in
1991.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, his agent said Maradona wanted to return to
Napoli as a player or player-manager, but the plan fell through
and Maradona's playing career is considered to be over.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Maradona received permission to leave Argentina for
two weeks to go to France where he is working as a World Cup
commentator for Argentine television. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
