<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pension Increase by Britain Insufficient: Gurkha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Former Gurkha soldiers who
served in the British army on Friday evening criticized the
planned increase of pensions for them by the British government as
"completely insufficient."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with BBC Nepali Service, Padam Bahadur Gurung,
president of the Gurkha Army Ex-Servicemen's Organization (GAESO),
said that they are demanding an increase of 500 percent, and the
demand has not been met.
</P>
<P>
The British government has decided to increase the pensions for
its former Gurkha soldiers which vary from 23 to 51 percent
depending on rank, years of service and date of retirement, the
British Embassy here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
There are 26,375 ex-Gurkhas and their families who are
receiving pensions worth 6.9 million British pounds (about 11
million U.S. dollars) every year from the British government, the
British Embassy said.
</P>
<P>
Many retired Gurkha soldiers are receiving as little as 24
pounds (38 dollars) per month while their British counterparts are
getting 475 pounds (760 dollars).
</P>
<P>
For the past four years, they have been demanding pension
parity with their British counterparts.
</P>
<P>
"We're not slaves, but employees of the British government, so
the pensions should be increased according to our demand on the
basis of the tri-partite agreement," Gurung argued.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement reached in 1947 between Nepal, India and
Britain, the British and Indian armies can recruit Nepalese, who
have been popularly known as Gurkha soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Gurung said that his organization has issued an ultimatum
threatening that if its demand is not met by June 15, it will
launch a three-phase movement. He did not elaborate on the
movement.
</P>
<P>
The GAESO had issued ultimata several times and had even
threatened to file its case at London courts.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Min Bahadur Gurung, vice-president of Nepal
Ex-Servicemen's Association, said on BBC that the proposed pension
increase is "completely insufficient."
</P>
<P>
He said that a movement will be launched after his association
meets.
</P>
<P>
The British army drafted Nepalese already in 1816 under the
Sugauli Treaty signed between Nepal and the East India Company of
Britain.
</P>
<P>
About 250,000 Nepalese soldiers fought during the First and
Second World Wars and 15,000 of them were killed.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 2,500 to 3,000 Nepalese are serving in the British
army.
</P>
<P>
For the past four years, the ex-Gurkhas have also been
demanding the right to live and work in Britain and pensions for
those dismissed without pensions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
