<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Envoy Rebukes U.S. Critics of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Li Zhaoxing, the Chinese
ambassador to the United States, Friday strongly criticized some
congressional critics of China just two weeks before U.S.
President Bill Clinton's trip to China.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference at the National Press Center that
Clinton's upcoming visit to China will further promote the
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Some lawmakers in Congress, using the Clinton administration's
China policy as a domestic political tool against Clinton, urged
the president to cancel or postpone his visit scheduled to start on
June 25.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the two sides are working very actively and
conscientiously to prepare for the upcoming visit.
</P>
<P>
"We are sure that... this visit will be yet another very
important one in our bilateral ties and will again make great
contribution to the further promotion of the relationship between
our countries," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of some congressional critics of China, Li dismissed
them as Cold War thinkers.
</P>
<P>
"After the Cold War, I believe, some of the people... seemed to
be nostalgic of the Cold War period. In other words, they found
that they still needed an enemy, they still needed a target, so as
to justify their Cold War mentality," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"So because these people were so keen to find an enemy, to find
find a substitute for the Soviet empire in the past, they had
started to look at China, which they should not look at,"Li said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China is pursuing a peaceful foreign policy.
"China presents no threat to any country, at all."
</P>
<P>
The ambassador denied U.S. intelligence information that
China's nuclear missiles are targeting American cities, saying
there's "nothing of the sort that I know of."
</P>
<P>
Clinton's five-city journey, from June 25 to July 3, will be
the first visit to China by an American president in a decade.
Clinton defended his trip on Thursday, citing a series of reasons
to justify his policies towards China.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that his trip is "the right thing to do for our
country."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador said recent events highlight the need
for closer U.S.-China consultations, including the tit-for-tat
nuclear testing in May by neighboring rivals India and Pakistan,
and the Asia financial crisis that has deeply devalued currencies
throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the fact that the Cold War is over, the issue of the
international stability has yet to be finally resolved," Li said.
"So two countries as important as China and America still have a
common responsibility and have a lot to do together," he affirmed.
</P>
<P>
China recently chaired a Geneva meeting of the five permanent
members of the U.N. Security Council, which condemned the nuclear
tests. Beijing also has agreed not to devalue its currency in
order to prevent another wave of financial destabilization.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of human rights, Li said, "China attaches the greatest
possible importance to human rights." He explained that for the
Chinese this means providing "the basic rights for people's
survival" or feeding the nation's 1.2 billion people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
