<HEADLINE> Dow Bounces Back, Wiping out Day's Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 12 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks staged a late
comeback Friday, with bargain-hunters coming back to buy cheap
shares and on confirmation of a recession in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average at one point was down 127.55
points at 8,684.22, on top of Thursday's decline of almost 160
points. That left Wall Street's best-known indicator almost 528
points below the record 9,211.84 reached May 13.
</P>
<P>
But the late buying wiped out the losses and the Dow finished
up 23.17 at 8,834.94 in active trading. Broader market indicators
were mixed.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 4.17 at 1,098.75, and
the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index was down 4.67 at
12,745.08,
</P>
<P>
Decliners outpaced advancers by a 12-to-7 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, where NYSE volume totaled 631.55 million
shares as against 603.47 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 1.17 to 566.67, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index dipped 1.65 to 697.40.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 2.79 at 441.55.
</P>
<P>
Yields on 30-year Treasuries stood at 5.67 percent, after
touching 5.64 percent, down from 5.65 percent late Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
