<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Distribution of Fertilizer Urged in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia National Farmers Union
(ZNFU) said Friday that the distribution of fertilizer should be
left to the private sector while the government should only
facilitate its importation into the country.
</P>
<P>
ZNFU's Acting Executive Director Songowayo Zyambo said here
the distribution of fertilizer should be put in private hands and
that a commercial court should be established to handle disputes
between private dealers and farmers.
</P>
<P>
Zyambo said a steering committee should be appointed to
monitor the whole distribution process to ensure that fertilizer
reaches every part of the country.
</P>
<P>
In the case of fertilizer, the government can assist to bring
it into the country but must not manage the distribution and
related procedures, he said.
</P>
<P>
The steering committee will ensure transparency, and monitor
the formation of cartels and put a check on bogus dealers and
mediate on complaints between farmers and companies involved in
the distribution of fertilizer, Zyambo said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government should only facilitate the acquisition
of inputs for small-scale farmers who desperately need
assistance.
</P>
<P>
The mechanisms for the distribution of fertilizer, he said,
should be planned collectively by dealers, farmers and the
government.
</P>
<P>
ZNFU will work closely with the government to make maize an
export crop as well as improve food security in the country, he
promised.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Agriculture, Food and Fisheries Minister
Amusaa Mwanamwambwa announced that the government will start
distributing fertilizer to all parts of the country because the
private sector was unable to handle the exercise in a
satisfactory manner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Rebukes Treasury Secretary for Secrecy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright has rebuked Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin in
a letter for failing to inform her about a money-laundering sting
operation in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
"I would appreciate being kept personally informed of
developing investigations in Mexico and other foreign countries
that could have a significant foreign policy fallout," Albright
said in the letter dated May 22.
</P>
<P>
"I do not wish to interfere with your law enforcement work, but
I do believe we need to do a better job of coordination," she
complained in the letter.
</P>
<P>
Albright expressed concern "about the negative tone this
development introduces into the relationship and that Mexican
cooperation on several fronts, particularly counternarcotics, may
be affected."
</P>
<P>
An Associated Press report said Friday the letter was inserted
in the Congressional Record by Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, but
it did not disclose how Grassley obtained the letter.
</P>
<P>
Albright wrote the letter following an uproar in Mexico touched
off by the disclosure that U.S. Customs agents working under
Rubin's jurisdiction had carried out part of the sting operation
without Mexican authorization.
</P>
<P>
Mexican bankers were arrested after being lured into the United
States under false pretenses. U.S. authorities seized 110 million
U.S. dollars and three Mexican banks were indicted in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Mexico has indicated that laws were broken by the agents and
that it plans to prosecute them.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton also has expressed regret to
Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo about the secrecy of the
operation, which was carried out over three years and was made
public last month.
</P>
<P>
Rubin had said that keeping Mexico uninformed about the
operation was deemed necessary to protect the agents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Extension of U.N. Mission in Bosnia Recommended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan recommended on Friday that the U.N. Mission in Bosnia-
Herzegovina (UNMIBH) stay there for one more year to help set up a
multi-ethnic police and a judicial system for all its citizens.
</P>
<P>
The UNMIBH, with its current mandate expiring at the end of
this month, comprises a 2,011 member police unit contributed by 42
countries with an aim to train and advise the newly established
local police forces.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, which was made public
Friday, Annan said the last three months have seen an increase in
violent incidents in Bosnia which are aimed at returning refugees
and displaced persons, especially those of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
UNMIBH "will do everything in its power to further advance the
restructuring of the local police forces in order to help create
confidence for returning minorities," the report said.
</P>
<P>
"However, it would be overly optimistic to expect a decisive
change before the nationwide elections scheduled for 13 September
1998," it said.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, some 20,000 refugees and
displaced people have returned to Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
Dealing with U.N. activities in the country since the 1995
Dayton Peace Accord which ended a war, Annan said the 5.1 billion
U.S. dollar reconstruction program endorsed by the World Bank
after the Dayton Accord "remains on track".
</P>
<P>
The Security Council is expected to adopt Annan's
recommendation on Monday, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard told
reporters on Friday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0202 </DOCNO>
