<HEADLINE> Tunisia Calls for Peaceful Solution to Conflicts Between Eritrea, Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Tunisian President Zine Al-Abidine Ben
Ali Friday reiterated his call on Eritrea and Ethiopia to solve their
border disputes through dialog, the Tunisia-Africa News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Ben Ali made the call during his separate meetings with Ethiopian
Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin and Eritrean Minister of Local
Government Mohamud S.
</P>
<P>
Mesfin and Sherifo arrived here Friday in their north African tours
to rally support for their stands on the disputes.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea gained independence from Ethiopia in 1993. Ever since then,
the two countries have been at odds over at least six border areas. On
May 6, armed clashes broke out between the two sides for a
400-square-kilometer rocky land.
</P>
<P>
During their meetings with Ben Ali, Mesfin and Sherifo conveyed him
messages from the presidents of their countries, asking for Tunisia's
efforts to help stop their armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Ben Ali expressed readiness to exert efforts to help the two
neighbors in the Horn of Africa settle the disputes in the framework
of the Organization of the African Unity, which has called for an
immediate ceasefire and a negotiation between the two countries.
</P>
