<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> . DeU8j!la Trying to Gain Faster Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The 1998/99 budgets of Kenya,
Uganda and Tanzania read at their respective parliaments Thursday
have spelled out far-reaching tough measures with an eye to
faster economic growth, local analysts said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The three East Africa Cooperation (EAC) members meshed their
budget calendars for the first time in a show of harmony to
symbolize the new-found spirit of the EAC treaty expected to be
signed by their heads of state in November.
</P>
<P>
All three have been struggling to cope with high costs of
devastated infrastructure as a result of drought earlier 1997 and
then months of El Nino rains and floods at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Tanzania have already missed their low revenue
targets this year, while Kenya suffers from a budget deficit
reaching 2.7 percent of gross domestic product in the 1997/98
fiscal year to end on June 30.
</P>
<P>
"I am asking all of you to tighten your belts so we can
achieve a balanced budget this year and thereafter achieve
surpluses," said Kenyan Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae in his
budget draft.
</P>
<P>
"We are faced with a daunting task of how to achieve faster
economic growth, preferably in excess of seven percent," he said.
Kenya's economic growth fell from 4.6 percent in 1996 to 2.3
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
He proposed a severe slash in public spending which is
estimated at 30.5 percent of GDP in 1997/98.
</P>
<P>
The painful measures include the retrenchment of 100,000 civil
servants and teachers, and the reduction of government borrowing
requirements by at least five percent.
</P>
<P>
Nyachae also vowed to speed up privatization, enforce the tax
system, improve infrastructure especially roads, keep inflation
within one single digit level and intensify fights against
corruption and tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
In new capital Dodoma in central Tanzania, Minister of State
in the President's Office Nassoro Malocho said just before the
budget reading that the country will focus on repairing the
infrastructure in the coming fiscal year during which economic
recovery would be slow.
</P>
<P>
"Our expectations for developments in 1998/99 are not
ambitious... Our development targets have been trimmed to
realistic levels in keeping with our ability as a nation to
deliver," he said,
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Finance Minister Daniel Yona said he expected to
raise 699.5 billion Tanzanian Shillings (1.076 billion U.S.
Dollars) in domestic revenue in 1998/99, or 13.4 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's economic growth rate in 1997/98 fiscal year is
estimated at 3.5 percent, below the target of 4.5 percent, while
revenue collection is expectedly to hit 627,500 million Tanzanian
Shillings (about 946 million Dollars), about 10 percent below the
target.
</P>
<P>
About 650 Tanzanian Shillings equal to one U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
Yona said the government plans to collect 695,165.9 million
Tanzanian Shillings from its domestic sources and spend 1,007,786
million Tanzanian Shillings in the coming fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
In Kampala, Ugandan Finance Minister Gerald Sendaula said that
Uganda will focus on five key areas of security, education,
roads, poverty eradication and pay reform in 1998/99.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's gross domestic product grew by 5.5 percent in
1997/98, up from 5.0 percent in 1996/97 but slower than the
targeted seven percent.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government now aims to increase its revenue
collection by 17.6 percent for 1998/99 to 940 billion Ugandan
Shillings (0.82 billion U.S. Dollars) from expected 798.8 billion
Ugandan Shillings in 1997/98, said Sendaula.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan budget remained cautious avoiding major policy
changes effected in last year's budget but with expected increase
on tax revenues, local analysts said.
</P>
<P>
"If we want more spending, we must face the reality of raising
the necessary funds domestically," said Sendaula.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government also intends to reduce the duty rates
on fuel and drinks in a bid to get closer to the levels of those
in its east African neighbors.
</P>
<P>
However, economic and tax harmonization on a broader scale
will be a formidable task among the three east African countries
where per capita income ranges from 200 to 300 U.S. Dollars a
year, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The tax take in Kenya's relatively industrialized economy, for
example, amounts to around 28 percent of GDP, while in Tanzania
and Uganda with more agricultural economies, the figure is close
to 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
Under the would-be EAC treaty, the three countries seeks to
eliminate internal tariffs by 2000, regularize external tariffs
and implement a customs union with five years starting from 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
