<HEADLINE> Israel Urged to Withdraw From South Lebanon Unconditionally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIRUT, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Speaker of the Australian House of
Representatives Ian Sinclair Friday called on Israel to withdraw from
south Lebanon unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair made the call when he was visiting the village of Qana
in South Lebanon, where 106 civilians were killed in Israeli raids
in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
He said any agreements or security arrangements Israel demands
should be negotiated after the Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
He called for an unconditional Israeli implementation of the
United Nations Security Council Resolution 425, which demands
unilateral Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, Israel decided to endorse the resolution. But it said
it would not pull back its troops unless security arrangements are
made with the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has rejected the offer, insisting that the withdrawal be
unconditional.
</P>
<P>
The Australian house speaker said that he hopes that the Qana
massacre would become an incentive for more efforts to make peace in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair, who arrived here Wednesday from Syria, has held talks
with Lebanese leaders on bilateral ties and regional affairs in his
three-day visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
