<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Says Russia on Right Course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 12 (Xinhua) -- President Boris Yeltsin said Friday
that Russia is on the right path and all the problems dogging the
country would eventually be overcome.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a grand reception in the Kremlin marking the Day of
Russia, Yeltsin said, "The history of a new, democratic Russia
began eight years ago. We have a glorious past stretching over
1,000 years and a great and happy future."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the declaration of Russia's sovereignty
eight years ago that marked the beginning of the breakup of the
former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
That day was formerly declared Russia's Independence Day, but
was later renamed as Day of Russia. "Russia had never been a
colony and there was no such thing as independence," a government
spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
In Yeltsin's address, which was broadcast live by state
television, the president said the past fews years "were a heavy
test for everyone of us. We had to overcome obstacles."
</P>
<P>
"It was difficult, but we have stayed on the course and did
not turn back."
</P>
<P>
However, Yeltsin acknowledged that changes in the years had not
resulted in a noticeable improvement in living conditions. "Russia
has not become a prosperous and stable economy nor are its
citizens well provided for or confident of their future," he said.
</P>
<P>
As Yeltsin made the speech, hundreds of miners were
demonstrating in blistering summer heat in central Moscow,
demanding that the government pay back their wages and Yeltsin
step down.
</P>
<P>
The miners, who were picketing the White House, the seat of
Russia's federal government, held such posters as: "Yeltsin, give
us our money back," and "Yeltsin, we brought you up, we will bring
you down."
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov has indicated that he is
prepared to talk with the miners if they give up political
demands, but they remain defiant.
</P>
<P>
Millions of Russian citizens, including teachers, doctors and
army officers, often have to wait months to get their salaries.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev told a news conference on Thursday that the government
owed miners some 3 billion rubles (500 million U.S.
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
