<HEADLINE> GM UAW Strike Expands, Workers Threaten Long Walkout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Auto Workers stepped
up its pressure on the General Motors Corp. Thursday night when
some 5,800 UAW members started their strike at the Delphi Flint
East complex, according to an AP report reaching here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The plant supplies parts for nearly every GM vehicle made in
the United States, Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The walkout came six days after UAW workers went on strike
across town at the Flint Metal Center, a stamping plant. That
strike has caused the layoffs of nearly 25,000 workers at two
dozen other plants. Effects of the strike have spread to nine
states, Mexico and Canada.
</P>
<P>
Most of GM's other North American assembly plants could be
affected by the end of next week, which will further affect other
parts plants owned by GM and its suppliers. GM, the No. one car
making giant in the United States, has 28 wholly owned major
assembly plants in North America with 296,500 hourly workers.
</P>
<P>
Jobs are the primary issue. The UAW fears GM may transfer work
out of both Flint plants or even close them. The Delphi plant is
considered especially vulnerable because the low-tech parts it
makes can be produced much more cheaply outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
GM also is considering moving production of its next generation
of small cars to a low-wage country from its big Lordstown, Ohio,
plant. And it has leaked that the automaker plans to double
production in Mexico over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Striking workers said they fear losing their jobs to overseas
workers.
</P>
<P>
GM said in a statement that it was disappointed the UAW had
decided to strike both plants. It said it "will have a ripple
effect on thousands of GM employees, vehicle consumers, supplier
facilities, stockholders and communities."
</P>
<P>
Some industrial analysts believed that the effect of a combined
strike could be greater than that of a 1996 strike because GM's
vehicle inventories are leaner. The 1996 strike lasted 17 days and
cost GM 900 million U.S. dollars after taxes.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that talks between negotiators of GM and the UAW
are scheduled to resume at both plants Friday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
