<HEADLINE> Popular Discussion on Land-Use Law Revision Encouraged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature has
received 577 letters on the draft of the revised Land-Use Law from
ordinary people, who concern themselves to the law, which has
bearing on their basic interests.
</P>
<P>
Many farmers, grass-roots rural officials, those in charge of
land-use management and township enterprises aired their views to
the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC),
said Bian Yaowu, vice-chairman of the Legislative Affairs
Commission of the NPC Standing Committee, today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 836 people signed on a letter to the most
authoritative body.
</P>
<P>
Within the one month after the draft law was promulgated, the
NPC Standing Committee summoned relevant officials, law and
economics experts and representatives from democratic parties to
discuss on the draft.
</P>
<P>
"The discussion pooled the wisdom of the people and will
guarantee the quality of the law-making," Bian said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the letters have showed consensus on the land
management system in accordance with the different uses, namely,
land for farming, construction and idle land. But some advocated
for clear legislative definitions with their use.
</P>
<P>
Bian went on to say that the new legislation for land-use would
include this kind of stipulations and safeguard the interests of
farmers.
</P>
<P>
Since 1986, China has adopted the existing land-use law, which
is considered somewhat unappropriate for the current market
economy.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee made public the draft law in early
May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
