<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Producers Prices Pick Up 0.2 Pct in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. prices paid to factories
and other producers rose 0.2 percent in May, reflecting a record
increase in prescription drugs and the first rise in energy costs
in eight months, the Labor Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted increase, matching the rise in April,
followed a string of five declines, according to the department.
Through the first five months of the year, finished goods costs
measured by the Producer Price Index (PPI) have fallen at an
annual rate of 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The monthly gain was largely attributed to a 10.7 percent
increase in prescription drugs, which in turn was driven by a 585
percent rise in a single class of drugs, minor tranquilizers, the
department said.
</P>
<P>
Without the prescription drug increase, producer prices overall
would have been unchanged.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report Friday, the Commerce Department said
business inventories rose a modest 0.2 percent in April. That's
much smaller than the increases of 0.6 percent in March and 0.7
percent in February.
</P>
<P>
Business sales declined 0.1 percent in April after a 0.7
percent increase in March.
</P>
<P>
Energy costs shot up 0.8 percent. It was all gasoline, up 4.3
percent. Heating oil fell 1.1 percent, and residential natural
gas, 0.5 percent. Electricity was unchanged. Energy costs last
increased in September.
</P>
<P>
Food prices fell 0.3 percent, reflecting a 20.9 percent drop in
vegetables, the most in 17 months. Lettuce, which had soared
earlier in the year when El Nino's rains washed out California
fields, came down 59 percent. Fruit, however, rose 2.3 percent.
Beef, pork and fish prices also increased.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile food and energy categories, prices
increased 0.2 percent, the same as for the overall index. That
reflected both the drug increase and a 2.8 percent rise in tobacco
costs. May's rise in tobacco followed a 3.4 percent rise the month
before. Tobacco companies are raising prices to pay the
multimillion-dollar cost of settling liability lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
Costs fell 0.1 percent at the intermediate level and 0.3
percent at the crude level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Still Against NATO Use of Force in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Russia expressed Friday its
opposition to NATO military intervention in Kosovo, claiming that
non-military means has not been exhausted.
</P>
<P>
Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeev told the press after the
NATO-Russia Permanent Joint Council that his country is trying to
look through other non-military means in the effort to help solve
the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Russian defense chief stressed that a United Nations
Security Council resolution is needed in the event of NATO use of
force.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever method to be used has to be in accordance with the
U.N. Security Council resolution," said the defense minister.
</P>
<P>
When asked how Russia would vote should there be a show of
hands in the U.N. headquarters, Sergeev said that it is only the
president who can answer this question.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who is scheduled to meet
Slobodan Milosevic, president of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia, early next week, is opposed to NATO use of force.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on the NATO pronounced mock air raids in
Albania and Macedonia, the Russian defense minister said that he
is not quite clear whether it is meant as a humanitarian manouver
or a demonstration of force.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana, who attended the joint
press briefing with Sergeev, said that the NATO aim is to find a
U.N. resolution in New York.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen, who said Thursday that it
is not imperative for NATO to get a U.N. mandate to resort to the
use of force, said at a separate briefing Friday that from two
days of meetings among defense ministers from NATO member states,
Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council member states as well as Russia
and Ukraine, he saw a broad consensus that a legal framework is
needed for outside military intervention.
</P>
<P>
But opinions differed among ministers as to whether it has to
be a U.N. resolution or a mandate by the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe or Article 51 of the U.N. Charter
itself.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that Russia would risk isolating itself in the
international community if it did not try to bring Milosevic to
the negotiating table. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economist Predicts Continuing Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese economist said today
that China's economy will continue to improve in the second half
of this year despite the influences of the shaky economic
situations in Japan and other countries in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
"China's economic growth in May was far from fortuitous and
resulted from effectiveness of measures the Chinese Government
adopted to stimulate domestic demand and promote investment in
infrastructure construction." according to Professor Cheng
Xiusheng from the State Council Development Research Center. Cheng
made the comments at today's symposium on regional economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show that China has recorded industrial
value-added of 776.8 billion yuan between January and May, up 7.9
percent on last year's same period. The May figure hit 168.1
billion yuan, a year-on-year rise of eight percent or slight
increase in the margin for April.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the economist also expressed concern about
devaluation of the Japanese Yen. "The negative impact of the
financial turmoil in Southeast Asia has begun to affect on the
Chinese's economy and the unexpected recession in Japan may
possibly spark another crisis in Asia," said Cheng.
</P>
<P>
China's export volume rose 5.4 percent in the first five months
of 1998, with the May falling by 1.5 percent, according to
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Analysts further noted that devaluation of Yen may reduce
Japan's domestic demand for Chinese products and could possibly
restrict to some extent the latter's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
However, Cheng expressed his belief investments in
infrastructure construction will be a major factor in increasing
the speed of China's economic locomotive.
</P>
<P>
"Investments will certainly outstrip levels for the first half
of this year and may even increase by more than 15 percent." Cheng
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
