<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Centennial of Independence, Jubilant Fete </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- National flags were displayed and
waved everywhere. White doves were released. Bells were tolled and
fireworks were set off. The Filipinos put on a fiesta Friday,
jubilantly celebrating the centennial of the country's
independence from Spain.
</P>
<P>
The celebration started early Friday. At 6 a.m., the people
were waked by simultaneous ringing of church bells and ship sirens
all over the country. Then President Fidel Ramos and
representatives from 32 countries and regions re-enacted the
proclamation of independence in Kawit, Cavite province, south of
Manila.
</P>
<P>
On the same day 100 years ago, General Emilio Aguinaldo, leader
of the revolutionary movement against the Spanish colonialists,
declared the country's independence in Kawit. Aguinaldo later
became the first president of the republic.
</P>
<P>
But according to history, the Philippines did not gain
independence immediately. Under the Treaty of Paris signed in
December 1898, Spain, which was defeated by the United States
after ruling the Philippines for about 330 years, ceded the
islands to the latter. It was until July 1946 that the Philippines
became an independent republic.
</P>
<P>
To let the Filipinos learn again the values of the country's
historic struggle for independence and use these for development
in the future, the Philippine government set June 12 as the
country's independence day, also called the national day, to imbue
people with patriotism.
</P>
<P>
At exactly 7 a.m., national flags were raised simultaneously
all over the country. Then sky-diving exhibitions, regattas and
other activities were held by the Manila Bay. In the presidential
palace, President Ramos toasted the occasion with diplomats and
dignitaries in a vin d'honneur at 11 a.m..
</P>
<P>
The celebration culminated in a grand centennial parade at the
Luneta Park in Manila. At 2:30 p.m. hundreds of thousands of
people had gathered at the park to join or witness the parade
which depicted the country's quest for freedom in a tableau of
color, costumes and creative floats.
</P>
<P>
In his centennial speech during the parade, President Ramos
said the first centennial was simply the beginning of greater
things to come to the Philippines as long as the people hold true
to unity and courage.
</P>
<P>
He said the country is standing on the threshold not only of a
new century, but of a new Filipinism, "a new sense of ourselves,
and our capabilities and our national destiny." He called on the
people to take the opportunity to renew themselves as a nation and
work for the country's future.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the parade, the people were treated to a
spectacular display of fireworks. In 30 minutes, about 19,000
shells of fireworks rocketed from four barges docked at the Manila
Bay, lighting up the skies with various patterns like
chrysanthemums, heart-shaped stars and the colors of the
Philippine national flag.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Tourism Secretary Mina Gabor said the fireworks show
was "unprecedented" in the Philippines' history because of its
color and shape, adding that the fireworks were synchronized to
about 25 local medley songs and controlled through a computer.
</P>
<P>
The Filipinos' centennial fever will stretch to the days after
June 12. According to the Philippine Centennial Commission,
various social sectors including the disabled and religious groups
will showcase the gains of the last 100 years on June 13, the
first day of the second century.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Expo Filipino, another highlight of the
celebrations, will be inaugurated by President Ramos and foreign
dignitaries at Clark Special Economic Zone, a former U.S. Air
Force base about two hours' drive north of Manila. A total of 15
countries will participate in the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines began preparing for the centennial five years
ago. In 1994, the government set up the Philippine Centennial
Commission and organized various activities including cultural
shows, trade fairs, exhibitions and sports activities this year.
</P>
<P>
"I would like this centennial to make every Filipino not only
aware of his past but proud of his past. It is very important that
the present generation pass on the torch to the next generation,"
said Salvador Laurel, chairman of the centennial commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
