<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agriculture Remains Pakistan's Economic Mainstay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The agricultural sector which is
the backbone of Pakistan's national economy, continues to hold the
 position in the next financial year.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the budgetary proposals for the fiscal 1998-1999
(July 1-June 30), Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz Friday told the
National Assembly that after exports the agricultural sector is
the second pillar of the strategy of economic growth and
self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the agriculture incentives package
announced in April 1997 has had encouraging results.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of agriculture rose from 0.1 percent in 1996-97
to 6 percent during the current year, he said, adding that record
production of wheat of 19 million tons and of sugarcane of 53
million tons have been realized during this year.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, he said, import of wheat for next year is likely
to be less than 1 million tons as against 4 million tons this
year.
</P>
<P>
"We are now self-sufficient in sugar and have also an
exportable surplus," he said.
</P>
<P>
Expressing concerns over the lower yield of cotton, he said
that if untimely heavy rains had not caused damage to the cotton
crop, agriculture's growth would have been over 6 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
