<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Defense Outlay Up Despite Financial Difficulties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has increased its
defense expenditure by 8.4 percent in the new fiscal year budget
(July 1-June 30) despite financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
According to the budget proposals presented by Finance Minister
Sartaj Aziz in the National Assembly Friday afternoon, the defense
expenditure for the 1998-99 fiscal year is 1.45 trillion rupees
(about 3.3 billion U.S. dollars), registering an 8.4-percent
increase over the revised estimates of the outgoing fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The defense outlay in the new budget accounts for 29.3 percent
of the government's current expenditure which has been estimated
at 4.957 trillion rupees (11.3 billion dollars). Together with an
expected debt servicing of 2.756 trillion rupees (6.3 billion
dollars), the two take up 84.8 percent of the current expenditure.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister said in his budget speech that "the brave
armed forces are prepared to face any challenge and it is our duty
to take full care of their needs."
</P>
<P>
He said national security is Pakistan's "first priority" as
"we are prepared to make any sacrifice for the security and
solidarity of our homeland."
</P>
<P>
"To strengthen national defense and upgrade defense capability
to a level that no one could look at us with malaise is a critical
element of our policy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said an outstanding feature of Pakistan's national
security is the success in the nuclear field. "We are committed to
use nuclear technology for peaceful purposes but will not tolerate
a situation in which the regional security balance is disturbed,"
he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Stresses Self-Reliance in Face of Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Finance Minister
Sartaj Aziz has urged the country to generate internal strength in
a liberal framework for guaranteeing economic and national
security and facing the sanctions bravely in a bid to achieve
self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the Federal Budget for 1998-99 (July 1-June 30) in
the National Assembly Friday afternoon, he stressed the need for
fiscal and financial sustainability. "Our economic growth should
be based on national resources and dependence on external means
should be minimized."
</P>
<P>
He said, "Our needs of food and other consumable items should
be met from domestic sources mainly and availability of energy
should be based on harnessing of natural resources." "The human
resource should be strengthened through education, particularly in
scientific and technical fields."
</P>
<P>
"We will continue with the liberal and deregulated framework of
our policies. Foreign investment, particularly in modern, hi-tech
and export industries, will be encouraged," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz noted that despite the difficult financial situation
together with the sanctions imposed by some Western nations in the
wake of Pakistan's nuclear tests late last month, Pakistan is
expected to achieve a 6-percent growth rate in GDP with 5.4
percent in agriculture and 7.2 percent in manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
To raise the level of investment to 18.7 percent of GDP, a
major portion of it, or 17.13 percent of GDP, will be generated
from domestic savings, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said Pakistan will further reduce the inflation rate
from 8.2 percent in the outgoing fiscal year to 8 percent in the
new fiscal year, expand exports by 15 percent, contain imports and
bring down the current account deficit to 1.5 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
The government has also set the target of further reducing the
budget deficit to 4.7 percent of GDP in the forthcoming fiscal
year from 5 percent of GDP in the current fiscal year, Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
The targets are difficult but not beyond reach, Aziz Saud,
adding that besides effective measures the government will
emphasize motivation of the private sector to increase production,
exports and investment.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the confidence that the private sector will give
its full support in ensuring economic growth and the people's
well-being.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the sanctions, he said that though they have
created temporary difficulties, "these have given us an
opportunity to review our traditional approach and look for other
alternatives."
</P>
<P>
"We should translate the determination and expectations of the
nation into a bold strategy capable of facing the new challenges.
I consider these sanctions as a blessing in disguise," the
minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
