<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Larger Winter Wheat Harvest Forecast in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The production of the U.S.
winter wheat is expected to be increased to 1.74 billion bushels
and more supplies in storage due to sluggish exports, the
Agriculture Department reported here Friday.
</P>
<P>
A larger-than-expected crop coupled with more wheat in stock is
likely to continue downward pressure on prices paid to farmers,
which have already hit a seven-year low this month.
</P>
<P>
The price forecast for all varieties of wheat is projected to
be around 3 U.S. dollars a bushel, down more than 1 dollar from
1997 (one bushel of wheat is about 27.24 kilograms).
</P>
<P>
The increased winter wheat estimate is largely due to improving
per-acre yield prospects, according to the department. Farmers are
now expecting to harvest almost 43 bushels of wheat an acre, which
would be second all-time only to last year's 45 bushels.
</P>
<P>
This boost in wheat production comes as exports are expected to
drop some 25 million bushels, mainly because of Asia's economic
crisis, which will translate into ending stocks of 827 million
bushels, up 61 million bushels from the May estimate.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. farmers are still expected to harvest 7
percent less wheat than in 1997. The total U.S. wheat crop is
forecast at 2.3 billion bushels.
</P>
<P>
The current estimate for the 1998 corn crop remained unchanged
from last month at 9.6 billion bushels (a bushel of corn is about
25.42 kilograms). The soybean projection was steady at 2.8 billion
bushels, which would be a record (a bushel of soybeans is some
27.216 kilograms).
</P>
<P>
Estimates for the U.S. corn crop remained virtually unchanged
from last month, including projected prices of up to 2.45 dollars
a bushel.
</P>
<P>
Soybean exports, however, were cut 30 million bushels compared
to the May estimate, which will leave a 10-year high of 425
million bushels in stock once this year's record large crop is
harvested.
</P>
<P>
Soybean prices are expected to remain steady at between 4.75
and 5.75 dollars a bushel.
</P>
<P>
The cotton forecast was lowered 1 million bales compared to
May, mainly because of adverse weather in California and Texas
(one bale of cotton is 480 pounds). Exports and domestic mill use
of cotton are both forecast below last year, and price is down
almost 5 cents a pound from 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
