<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approaches New Loan Agreement With Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Poul Thomsen, chief negotiator
for Romania of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), will come to
Bucharest next week to approach a possible new stand-by loan
agreement with the Romanian government.
</P>
<P>
Making the announcement here Friday, IMF representative here
John Hill said that the IMF will send five experts to Bucharest,
who will hold talks primarily on how faithful Romania is to its
governing program over 1998-1999 and whether it is possible to
conclude a new agreement.
</P>
<P>
The latest stand-by agreement Romania concluded with the IMF
expired in May. The agreement, amounting to 301.5 million DST, was
divided in five instalments and could be delivered only if
economic and legislative criteria were satisfied. Romania hasn't
drawn but two of them standing for 120.6 million.
</P>
<P>
Four loan agreements were concluded after 1990 between Romania
and the monetary body but none came to its normal end because the
Romanian party fell short of observing its initial commitments.
</P>
<P>
Romanian Prime Minister Radu Vasile said after his latest
meeting with Poul Thomsen on April that Romania wished to conclude
with the IMF an 18-month agreement instead of 13-month in the
previous agreements, and so did Finance Minister Daniel Daianu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980613.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Killing of Ugandan Students Condemned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking U.N.
official Friday strongly condemned the killing of 80 students this
week in western Uganda, according to a U.N. spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Special Representative of the U.N. Secretary-General for
Children and Armed Conflict Olara Otunnu expressed his deep
concern about the plight of children affected by the ongoing
conflict situations in northern and western parts of Uganda, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The continuing abuse and brutalization of children, including
abduction, maiming, displacement and deprivation of education and
medial care is unacceptable," Otunnu was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Otunnu called for adherence by relevant international
conventions on children and for the treatment of schools and
hospitals as conflict-free zones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
