<HEADLINE> World Court Rules on Bakassi Peninsula </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The International Court of Justice
at the Hague of the Netherlands, ruled Thursday that it has
jurisdiction over the dispute between Nigeria and Cameroun over
the Bakassi Peninsula, which is claimed by both countries.
</P>
<P>
The dispute over the oil rich Bakassi in the Altantic was
filed at the international court by Cameroun in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In December 1995, Nigeria filed a preliminary objection on the
jurisdiction of the international court, on the ground that
Cameroun had extended its claim to Nigeria territory, a stretch
of over 1,800 kilometers from the Altantic to Lake Chad Basin.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria also objected on the ground that the dispute could be
handled through bilateral talks or within the Lake Chad Basin
Commission.
</P>
<P>
The dispute has resulted in incessant clashes between Nigeria
and Camerounian troops since 1993.
</P>
<P>
By the ruling of the court Thursday, the two countries are now
obligated to present their claims and evidences to the court,
local press reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The hearing of the case may last for several years, reports
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
