<HEADLINE> Nigeria's New Leader to Meet Parties on Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's new leader General
Abdulsalam Abubakar will meet leaders of the country's five
political parties Saturday on the transition to civil rule
program.
</P>
<P>
Chief Ogbuefi Ozomgbachi, national secretary of the
Grass-roots Democratic Movement, has confirmed the receipt of an
invitation letter dated June 10, The Punch newspaper reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting Saturday is believed to be part of the
consultations now going on concerning the transition program,
under which a presidential election is to be held on August 1.
</P>
<P>
The death of late leader General Sani Abacha, however, has
deprived the parties' sole candidate for the election.
</P>
<P>
General Abubakar has pledged to continue with Abacha's
transition program, for which, he said he will consult with all
relevant agencies at the highest level.
</P>
<P>
The country's pro-democracy groups, however, has urged
Abubakar to forget about the transition and hand over power to
Moshood Abiola, the beloved winner of the June 12, 1993 election
annulled by the then military government.
</P>
<P>
Abiola was put into jail by the Abacha government on June 23,
1994, when he announced himself the president of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The pro-democracy groups have vowed to go on with their mass
rallies nationwide Friday to mark the June 12 election, despite
stiff warning from the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
