<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan to Open U.N. Conference on Criminal Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan goes to Rome, Italy, Monday to open the U.N. Diplomatic
Conference on the establishment of the international criminal
court, his spokesman announced here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The four-day meeting will discuss issues related to the
creation of a permanent judicial institution with a global
jurisdiction to try individuals for war crimes and crimes against
humanity.
</P>
<P>
"The idea now is to create such a court by agreement among
states in the forms of an international treaty," according to a
U.N. backgrounder.
</P>
<P>
A 13-part, 116-article draft statute for the legal body is put
forward for discussion, with a number of political issues
remaining unsolved.
</P>
<P>
They include whether or not state consent would apply with
inherent jurisdiction of the court, whether the prosecutor would
be able to initiate criminal action independent of the Security
Council or the complaint of any state, the backgrounder said.
</P>
<P>
Other issues include whether the Security Council could stop the
course of investigation or prosecution if it considered it a
matter of international peace and security, the definition of war
crimes and whether or not to include the crime or aggression under
the jurisdiction of the court.
</P>
<P>
The conference is expected to finalize and approve a draft
convention to establish the court and the text will be submitted
to the U.N. General Assembly later this year for its
consideration.
</P>
<P>
Annan stays in Rome until Wednesday. He is also scheduled to
open a conference Monday on "crisis management and the NATO reform
-- the test-case of Bosnia for collective security in the next
century." 
</P>
</TEXT>
