<HEADLINE> Contact Group Ministers Meet on Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Western members of the six-nation
Contact Group comprising the United States, Russia, Britain,
France, Germany and Italy Friday approved new sanctions against
Yugoslavia, but Russia voiced opposition to these new sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the final press conference after the special
foreign ministers meeting, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
said, "President (Slobodan) Milosevic will be making a grave
mistake if he imagines that the international community will be as
slow to respond in Kosovo as it was in Bosnia."
</P>
<P>
Under the final statement, foreign ministers from the United
States, Germany, France, Italy and Britain confirmed their
decision to implement the ban on new investment in Serbia and
freeze funds held abroad by the Belgrade government.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to take steps to ban flights by Yugoslav
carriers between the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and their
countries.
</P>
<P>
However, Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov made it
clear that Russia was opposed to all these punishment measures and
possible use of force against Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Primakov told reporters after the meeting, "Measures are being
considered against Yugoslavia. We are against these measures, but
at the same time, there will be an exceptionally important meeting
with Milosevic."
</P>
<P>
Primakove was referring to the meeting between Russian
President Boris Yeltsin and President Milosevic due to take place
in Moscow next week.
</P>
<P>
All the Contact Group ministers "welcomed the invitation by
President Yeltsin to President Milosevic and stressed the
importance of President Milosevic taking advantage of this meeting
to announce progress." 
</P>
</TEXT>
