<HEADLINE> Shuttle Discovery Returns to Earth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. space shuttle Discovery
landed Friday on time at 2 P.M. in Kennedy Space Center, Florida,
concluding NASA's final docking with the Russian Mir Station and
bringing back the last American astronaut Andrew Thomas.
</P>
<P>
Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer, a high energy particle detector
designed and manufactured by scientists from China, the United
States and other countries, also was back on Earth.
</P>
<P>
During its 10-day experiment, AMS worked smoothly and even
better than previously predicted. The aim of AMS experiment is to
look for both antimatter and "dark matter." This particle detector
will be placed on the future International Space Station for
further test in 2002.
</P>
<P>
After 141 days in orbit, the 46-year-old and an Australian-born
engineer, Thomas couldn't wait to indulge in some Earthly
pleasures, eating ice cream and a stroll on the beach, seeing
sunshine.
</P>
<P>
During NASA's nine docking missions to Mir, 43 Americans who
visited the Mir Station and seven Americans who lived on Mir spent
977 days in space. The docking program has provided experience for
the building of International Space Station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
