<HEADLINE> IMF to Approach New Loan Agreement with Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Poul Thomsen, chief negotiator
for Romania of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), will come to
Bucharest next week for approaching a possible new stand-by loan
agreement with the Romanian government, IMF representative John
Hill announced here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Hill added that the IMF will send five experts to Bucharest,
who will hold talks primarily on how faithful Romania is to its
governing program over 1998-1999 and whether it is possible to
conclude a new agreement.
</P>
<P>
Four loan agreements have been concluded since 1990 between
Romania and the monetary body, but none came to its normal end
because the Romanian party fell short of observing its initial
commitments.
</P>
<P>
The latest stand-by agreement Romania concluded with the IMF
expired in May. The agreement was divided in five instalments and
could be delivered only if economic and legislative criteria were
satisfied.
</P>
<P>
Romanian Prime Minister Radu Vasile said after his latest
meeting with Poul Thomsen on April that Romania wished to conclude
with the IMF an 18-month agreement instead of the 13-month in the
previous agreements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
