<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian FM Rejects Direct Talks With Eritrea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin
Friday rejected a call by Eritrea for direct talks with Ethiopia on an
end to their border war.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark upon his arrival here Friday evening for talks
with Egyptian officials on his country's border conflicts with
Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Direct talks are unacceptable while "occupation" is going on, he
was quoted by Egypt's Middle East News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mesfin described the clashes between the two countries as
"explosive" and accused Eritrea of aggression.
</P>
<P>
Showing support to a peace plan proposed by the U.S. and Rwanda and
backed by the Organization of African Unity (OAU), he said Eritrea's
rejection made it difficult to reach a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
The main feature of the four-point U.S.-Rwandan peace proposal is
Eritrea's retreat from the Badme area, under Eritrean control since
May 12, to its 1994 borders, and the reinstatement of the Ethiopian
administration.
</P>
<P>
"The Rwandan-U.S. initiative is still valid. Ethiopia will#o its
best to reach a peaceful solution to the crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea have argued peacefully over their border for
years, but the dispute turned violent on May 6, with each side
accusing the other of incursions. Hundreds of people were reportedly
killed.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian envoy is expected to meet with his Egyptian
counterpart Amr Moussa later Friday and will deliver a message from
Prime Minister Meles Zenawi to Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Mesfin paid a one-day visit to Tunisia Thursday where he expounded
his country's viewpoint regarding the Ethiopian-Eritrean border
dispute.
</P>
<P>
He visit came one day after Eritrean Minister of Local
Government Mohamod Sherifo left Cairo after handing over a message to
Mubarak from Eritrean President Issayas Aferwerki.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean minister had asked Mubarak for mediation within the
African initiative to end the devastating struggle between the two
neighboring countries in the Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has sent two messages to leaders of both Eritrea and
Ethiopia, calling for an immediate end to fighting to make way for
African mediation.
</P>
<P>
The two countries, among the world's poorest, are at odds oveIt
least six areas along their common border. Eritrea gained independence
from Ethiopia in 1993. Their current border row centers on a 400
square kilometers rocky triangle of land along their western border.
</P>
<P>
The OAU has reportedly agreed to send a high-level mediation
team to the disputed border area between Ethiopian and Eritrea for
mediation to end the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
The delegation may include six African heads of state on
mediation efforts in Asmara and Addis Ababa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
